00134 // The user can define the following macros in the build script to
00135 // control Google Test's behavior.  If the user doesn't define a macro
00136 // in this list, Google Test will define it.
00137 //
00138 //   GTEST_HAS_CLONE          - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that clone(2)
00139 //                              is/isn't available.
00140 //   GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS     - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that exceptions
00141 //                              are enabled.
00142 //   GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING  - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that ::string
00143 //                              is/isn't available (some systems define
00144 //                              ::string, which is different to std::string).
00145 //   GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that ::string
00146 //                              is/isn't available (some systems define
00147 //                              ::wstring, which is different to std::wstring).
00148 //   GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE       - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that POSIX regular
00149 //                              expressions are/aren't available.
00150 //   GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD        - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that <pthread.h>
00151 //                              is/isn't available.
00152 //   GTEST_HAS_RTTI           - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that RTTI is/isn't
00153 //                              enabled.
00154 //   GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING    - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that
00155 //                              std::wstring does/doesn't work (Google Test can
00156 //                              be used where std::wstring is unavailable).
00157 //   GTEST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE      - Define it to 1/0 to indicate tr1::tuple
00158 //                              is/isn't available.
00159 //   GTEST_HAS_SEH            - Define it to 1/0 to indicate whether the
00160 //                              compiler supports Microsoft's "Structured
00161 //                              Exception Handling".
00162 //   GTEST_HAS_STREAM_REDIRECTION
00163 //                            - Define it to 1/0 to indicate whether the
00164 //                              platform supports I/O stream redirection using
00165 //                              dup() and dup2().
00166 //   GTEST_USE_OWN_TR1_TUPLE  - Define it to 1/0 to indicate whether Google
00167 //                              Test's own tr1 tuple implementation should be
00168 //                              used.  Unused when the user sets
00169 //                              GTEST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE to 0.
00170 //   GTEST_LINKED_AS_SHARED_LIBRARY
00171 //                            - Define to 1 when compiling tests that use
00172 //                              Google Test as a shared library (known as
00173 //                              DLL on Windows).
00174 //   GTEST_CREATE_SHARED_LIBRARY
00175 //                            - Define to 1 when compiling Google Test itself
00176 //                              as a shared library.
00177 
00178 // This header defines the following utilities:
00179 //
00180 // Macros indicating the current platform (defined to 1 if compiled on
00181 // the given platform; otherwise undefined):
00182 //   GTEST_OS_AIX      - IBM AIX
00183 //   GTEST_OS_CYGWIN   - Cygwin
00184 //   GTEST_OS_HPUX     - HP-UX
00185 //   GTEST_OS_LINUX    - Linux
00186 //     GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID - Google Android
00187 //   GTEST_OS_MAC      - Mac OS X
00188 //   GTEST_OS_NACL     - Google Native Client (NaCl)
00189 //   GTEST_OS_SOLARIS  - Sun Solaris
00190 //   GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN  - Symbian
00191 //   GTEST_OS_WINDOWS  - Windows (Desktop, MinGW, or Mobile)
00192 //     GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_DESKTOP  - Windows Desktop
00193 //     GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MINGW    - MinGW
00194 //     GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE   - Windows Mobile
00195 //   GTEST_OS_ZOS      - z/OS
00196 //
00197 // Among the platforms, Cygwin, Linux, Max OS X, and Windows have the
00198 // most stable support.  Since core members of the Google Test project
00199 // don't have access to other platforms, support for them may be less
00200 // stable.  If you notice any problems on your platform, please notify
00201 // googletestframework@googlegroups.com (patches for fixing them are
00202 // even more welcome!).
00203 //
00204 // Note that it is possible that none of the GTEST_OS_* macros are defined.
00205 //
00206 // Macros indicating available Google Test features (defined to 1 if
00207 // the corresponding feature is supported; otherwise undefined):
00208 //   GTEST_HAS_COMBINE      - the Combine() function (for value-parameterized
00209 //                            tests)
00210 //   GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST   - death tests
00211 //   GTEST_HAS_PARAM_TEST   - value-parameterized tests
00212 //   GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST   - typed tests
00213 //   GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST_P - type-parameterized tests
00214 //   GTEST_USES_POSIX_RE    - enhanced POSIX regex is used. Do not confuse with
00215 //                            GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE (see above) which users can
00216 //                            define themselves.
00217 //   GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE   - our own simple regex is used;
00218 //                            the above two are mutually exclusive.
00219 //   GTEST_CAN_COMPARE_NULL - accepts untyped NULL in EXPECT_EQ().
00220 //
00221 // Macros for basic C++ coding:
00222 //   GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ - for disabling a gcc warning.
00223 //   GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_  - declares that a class' instances or a
00224 //                              variable don't have to be used.
00225 //   GTEST_DISALLOW_ASSIGN_   - disables operator=.
00226 //   GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_ - disables copy ctor and operator=.
00227 //   GTEST_MUST_USE_RESULT_   - declares that a function's result must be used.
00228 //
00229 // Synchronization:
00230 //   Mutex, MutexLock, ThreadLocal, GetThreadCount()
00231 //                  - synchronization primitives.
00232 //   GTEST_IS_THREADSAFE - defined to 1 to indicate that the above
00233 //                         synchronization primitives have real implementations
00234 //                         and Google Test is thread-safe; or 0 otherwise.
00235 //
00236 // Template meta programming:
00237 //   is_pointer     - as in TR1; needed on Symbian and IBM XL C/C++ only.
00238 //   IteratorTraits - partial implementation of std::iterator_traits, which
00239 //                    is not available in libCstd when compiled with Sun C++.
00240 //
00241 // Smart pointers:
00242 //   scoped_ptr     - as in TR2.
00243 //
00244 // Regular expressions:
00245 //   RE             - a simple regular expression class using the POSIX
00246 //                    Extended Regular Expression syntax on UNIX-like
00247 //                    platforms, or a reduced regular exception syntax on
00248 //                    other platforms, including Windows.
00249 //
00250 // Logging:
00251 //   GTEST_LOG_()   - logs messages at the specified severity level.
00252 //   LogToStderr()  - directs all log messages to stderr.
00253 //   FlushInfoLog() - flushes informational log messages.
00254 //
00255 // Stdout and stderr capturing:
00256 //   CaptureStdout()     - starts capturing stdout.
00257 //   GetCapturedStdout() - stops capturing stdout and returns the captured
00258 //                         string.
00259 //   CaptureStderr()     - starts capturing stderr.
00260 //   GetCapturedStderr() - stops capturing stderr and returns the captured
00261 //                         string.
00262 //
00263 // Integer types:
00264 //   TypeWithSize   - maps an integer to a int type.
00265 //   Int32, UInt32, Int64, UInt64, TimeInMillis
00266 //                  - integers of known sizes.
00267 //   BiggestInt     - the biggest signed integer type.
00268 //
00269 // Command-line utilities:
00270 //   GTEST_FLAG()       - references a flag.
00271 //   GTEST_DECLARE_*()  - declares a flag.
00272 //   GTEST_DEFINE_*()   - defines a flag.
00273 //   GetArgvs()         - returns the command line as a vector of strings.
00274 //
00275 // Environment variable utilities:
00276 //   GetEnv()             - gets the value of an environment variable.
00277 //   BoolFromGTestEnv()   - parses a bool environment variable.
00278 //   Int32FromGTestEnv()  - parses an Int32 environment variable.
00279 //   StringFromGTestEnv() - parses a string environment variable.
00280

00302 // Determines the version of gcc that is used to compile this.
00303 #ifdef __GNUC__
00304 // 40302 means version 4.3.2.
00305 # define GTEST_GCC_VER_ \
00306     (__GNUC__*10000 + __GNUC_MINOR__*100 + __GNUC_PATCHLEVEL__)
00307 #endif  // __GNUC__

00309 // Determines the platform on which Google Test is compiled.
00310 #ifdef __CYGWIN__
00311 # define GTEST_OS_CYGWIN 1
00312 #elif defined __SYMBIAN32__
00313 # define GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN 1
00314 #elif defined _WIN32
00315 # define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS 1
00316 # ifdef _WIN32_WCE
00317 #  define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE 1
00318 # elif defined(__MINGW__) || defined(__MINGW32__)
00319 #  define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MINGW 1
00320 # else
00321 #  define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_DESKTOP 1
00322 # endif  // _WIN32_WCE
00323 #elif defined __APPLE__
00324 # define GTEST_OS_MAC 1
00325 #elif defined __linux__
00326 # define GTEST_OS_LINUX 1
00327 # ifdef ANDROID
00328 #  define GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID 1
00329 # endif  // ANDROID
00330 #elif defined __MVS__
00331 # define GTEST_OS_ZOS 1
00332 #elif defined(__sun) && defined(__SVR4)
00333 # define GTEST_OS_SOLARIS 1
00334 #elif defined(_AIX)
00335 # define GTEST_OS_AIX 1
00336 #elif defined(__hpux)
00337 # define GTEST_OS_HPUX 1
00338 #elif defined __native_client__
00339 # define GTEST_OS_NACL 1
00340 #endif  // __CYGWIN__

00342 // Brings in definitions for functions used in the testing::internal::posix
00343 // namespace (read, write, close, chdir, isatty, stat). We do not currently
00344 // use them on Windows Mobile.
00345 #if !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
00346 // This assumes that non-Windows OSes provide unistd.h. For OSes where this
00347 // is not the case, we need to include headers that provide the functions
00348 // mentioned above.
00349 # include <unistd.h>
00350 # if !GTEST_OS_NACL
00351 // TODO(vladl@google.com): Remove this condition when Native Client SDK adds
00352 // strings.h (tracked in
00353 // http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=1175).
00354 #  include <strings.h>  // Native Client doesn't provide strings.h.
00355 # endif
00356 #elif !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
00357 # include <direct.h>
00358 # include <io.h>
00359 #endif

00361 // Defines this to true iff Google Test can use POSIX regular expressions.
00362 #ifndef GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE
00363 # define GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE (!GTEST_OS_WINDOWS)
00364 #endif

00368 // On some platforms, <regex.h> needs someone to define size_t, and
00369 // won't compile otherwise.  We can #include it here as we already
00370 // included <stdlib.h>, which is guaranteed to define size_t through
00371 // <stddef.h>.
00372 # include <regex.h>  // NOLINT
00373 
00374 # define GTEST_USES_POSIX_RE 1
00375 
00376 #elif GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
00377 
00378 // <regex.h> is not available on Windows.  Use our own simple regex
00379 // implementation instead.
00380 # define GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE 1
00381 
00382 #else
00383 
00384 // <regex.h> may not be available on this platform.  Use our own
00385 // simple regex implementation instead.
00386 # define GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE 1
00387 
00388 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE

00390 #ifndef GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
00391 // The user didn't tell us whether exceptions are enabled, so we need
00392 // to figure it out.
00393 # if defined(_MSC_VER) || defined(__BORLANDC__)
00394 // MSVC's and C++Builder's implementations of the STL use the _HAS_EXCEPTIONS
00395 // macro to enable exceptions, so we'll do the same.
00396 // Assumes that exceptions are enabled by default.
00397 #  ifndef _HAS_EXCEPTIONS
00398 #   define _HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
00399 #  endif  // _HAS_EXCEPTIONS
00400 #  define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS _HAS_EXCEPTIONS
00401 # elif defined(__GNUC__) && __EXCEPTIONS
00402 // gcc defines __EXCEPTIONS to 1 iff exceptions are enabled.
00403 #  define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
00404 # elif defined(__SUNPRO_CC)
00405 // Sun Pro CC supports exceptions.  However, there is no compile-time way of
00406 // detecting whether they are enabled or not.  Therefore, we assume that
00407 // they are enabled unless the user tells us otherwise.
00408 #  define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
00409 # elif defined(__IBMCPP__) && __EXCEPTIONS
00410 // xlC defines __EXCEPTIONS to 1 iff exceptions are enabled.
00411 #  define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
00412 # elif defined(__HP_aCC)
00413 // Exception handling is in effect by default in HP aCC compiler. It has to
00414 // be turned of by +noeh compiler option if desired.
00415 #  define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
00416 # else
00417 // For other compilers, we assume exceptions are disabled to be
00418 // conservative.
00419 #  define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 0
00420 # endif  // defined(_MSC_VER) || defined(__BORLANDC__)
00421 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
00422 
00423 #if !defined(GTEST_HAS_STD_STRING)
00424 // Even though we don't use this macro any longer, we keep it in case
00425 // some clients still depend on it.
00426 # define GTEST_HAS_STD_STRING 1
00427 #elif !GTEST_HAS_STD_STRING
00428 // The user told us that ::std::string isn't available.
00429 # error "Google Test cannot be used where ::std::string isn't available."
00430 #endif  // !defined(GTEST_HAS_STD_STRING)
00431 
00432 #ifndef GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
00433 // The user didn't tell us whether ::string is available, so we need
00434 // to figure it out.
00435 
00436 # define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING 0
00437 
00438 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
00439 
00440 #ifndef GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
00441 // The user didn't tell us whether ::std::wstring is available, so we need
00442 // to figure it out.
00443 // TODO(wan@google.com): uses autoconf to detect whether ::std::wstring
00444 //   is available.
00445 
00446 // Cygwin 1.7 and below doesn't support ::std::wstring.
00447 // Solaris' libc++ doesn't support it either.  Android has
00448 // no support for it at least as recent as Froyo (2.2).
00449 # define GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING \
00450     (!(GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID || GTEST_OS_CYGWIN || GTEST_OS_SOLARIS))
00451 
00452 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
00453 
00454 #ifndef GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
00455 // The user didn't tell us whether ::wstring is available, so we need
00456 // to figure it out.
00457 # define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING \
00458     (GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING && GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING)
00459 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
00460 
00461 // Determines whether RTTI is available.
00462 #ifndef GTEST_HAS_RTTI
00463 // The user didn't tell us whether RTTI is enabled, so we need to
00464 // figure it out.
00465 
00466 # ifdef _MSC_VER
00467 
00468 #  ifdef _CPPRTTI  // MSVC defines this macro iff RTTI is enabled.
00469 #   define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 1
00470 #  else
00471 #   define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 0
00472 #  endif
00473 
00474 // Starting with version 4.3.2, gcc defines __GXX_RTTI iff RTTI is enabled.
00475 # elif defined(__GNUC__) && (GTEST_GCC_VER_ >= 40302)
00476 
00477 #  ifdef __GXX_RTTI
00478 #   define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 1
00479 #  else
00480 #   define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 0
00481 #  endif  // __GXX_RTTI
00482 
00483 // Starting with version 9.0 IBM Visual Age defines __RTTI_ALL__ to 1 if
00484 // both the typeid and dynamic_cast features are present.
00485 # elif defined(__IBMCPP__) && (__IBMCPP__ >= 900)
00486 
00487 #  ifdef __RTTI_ALL__
00488 #   define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 1
00489 #  else
00490 #   define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 0
00491 #  endif
00492 
00493 # else
00494 
00495 // For all other compilers, we assume RTTI is enabled.
00496 #  define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 1
00497 
00498 # endif  // _MSC_VER
00499 
00500 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_RTTI
00501 
00502 // It's this header's responsibility to #include <typeinfo> when RTTI
00503 // is enabled.
00504 #if GTEST_HAS_RTTI
00505 # include <typeinfo>
00506 #endif

00508 // Determines whether Google Test can use the pthreads library.
00509 #ifndef GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
00510 // The user didn't tell us explicitly, so we assume pthreads support is
00511 // available on Linux and Mac.
00512 //
00513 // To disable threading support in Google Test, add -DGTEST_HAS_PTHREAD=0
00514 // to your compiler flags.
00515 # define GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD (GTEST_OS_LINUX || GTEST_OS_MAC || GTEST_OS_HPUX)
00516 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
00517 
00518 #if GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
00519 // gtest-port.h guarantees to #include <pthread.h> when GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD is
00520 // true.
00521 # include <pthread.h>  // NOLINT
00522 
00523 // For timespec and nanosleep, used below.
00524 # include <time.h>  // NOLINT
00525 #endif

00527 // Determines whether Google Test can use tr1/tuple.  You can define
00528 // this macro to 0 to prevent Google Test from using tuple (any
00529 // feature depending on tuple with be disabled in this mode).
00530 #ifndef GTEST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE
00531 // The user didn't tell us not to do it, so we assume it's OK.
00532 # define GTEST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE 1
00533 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE
00534 
00535 // Determines whether Google Test's own tr1 tuple implementation
00536 // should be used.
00537 #ifndef GTEST_USE_OWN_TR1_TUPLE
00538 // The user didn't tell us, so we need to figure it out.
00539 
00540 // We use our own TR1 tuple if we aren't sure the user has an
00541 // implementation of it already.  At this time, GCC 4.0.0+ and MSVC
00542 // 2010 are the only mainstream compilers that come with a TR1 tuple
00543 // implementation.  NVIDIA's CUDA NVCC compiler pretends to be GCC by
00544 // defining __GNUC__ and friends, but cannot compile GCC's tuple
00545 // implementation.  MSVC 2008 (9.0) provides TR1 tuple in a 323 MB
00546 // Feature Pack download, which we cannot assume the user has.
00547 # if (defined(__GNUC__) && !defined(__CUDACC__) && (GTEST_GCC_VER_ >= 40000)) \
00548     || _MSC_VER >= 1600
00549 #  define GTEST_USE_OWN_TR1_TUPLE 0
00550 # else
00551 #  define GTEST_USE_OWN_TR1_TUPLE 1
00552 # endif
00553 
00554 #endif  // GTEST_USE_OWN_TR1_TUPLE
00555

00557 // gtest-port.h's responsibility to #include the header implementing
00558 // tr1/tuple.
00559 #if GTEST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE

00602 // The compiler used in Symbian has a bug that prevents us from declaring the
00603 // tuple template as a friend (it complains that tuple is redefined).  This
00604 // hack bypasses the bug by declaring the members that should otherwise be
00605 // private as public.
00606 // Sun Studio versions < 12 also have the above bug.
00607 #if defined(__SYMBIAN32__) || (defined(__SUNPRO_CC) && __SUNPRO_CC < 0x590)
00608 # define GTEST_DECLARE_TUPLE_AS_FRIEND_ public:
00609 #else
00610 # define GTEST_DECLARE_TUPLE_AS_FRIEND_ \
00611     template <GTEST_10_TYPENAMES_(U)> friend class tuple; \
00612    private:
00613 #endif
00614 
00615 // GTEST_n_TUPLE_(T) is the type of an n-tuple.
00616 #define GTEST_0_TUPLE_(T) tuple<>
00617 #define GTEST_1_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, void, void, void, void, void, void, \
00618     void, void, void>
00619 #define GTEST_2_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, T##1, void, void, void, void, void, \
00620     void, void, void>
00621 #define GTEST_3_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, T##1, T##2, void, void, void, void, \
00622     void, void, void>
00623 #define GTEST_4_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, T##1, T##2, T##3, void, void, void, \
00624     void, void, void>
00625 #define GTEST_5_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, T##1, T##2, T##3, T##4, void, void, \
00626     void, void, void>
00627 #define GTEST_6_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, T##1, T##2, T##3, T##4, T##5, void, \
00628     void, void, void>
00629 #define GTEST_7_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, T##1, T##2, T##3, T##4, T##5, T##6, \
00630     void, void, void>
00631 #define GTEST_8_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, T##1, T##2, T##3, T##4, T##5, T##6, \
00632     T##7, void, void>
00633 #define GTEST_9_TUPLE_(T) tuple<T##0, T##1, T##2, T##3, T##4, T##5, T##6, \

00676 // ByRef<T>::type is T if T is a reference; otherwise it's const T&.
00677 template <typename T>
00678 struct ByRef { typedef const T& type; };  // NOLINT
00679 template <typename T>
00680 struct ByRef<T&> { typedef T& type; };  // NOLINT
00681 
00682 // A handy wrapper for ByRef.
00683 #define GTEST_BY_REF_(T) typename ::std::tr1::gtest_internal::ByRef<T>::type
00684 
00685 // AddRef<T>::type is T if T is a reference; otherwise it's T&.  This
00686 // is the same as tr1::add_reference<T>::type.
00687 template <typename T>
00688 struct AddRef { typedef T& type; };  // NOLINT
00689 template <typename T>
00690 struct AddRef<T&> { typedef T& type; };  // NOLINT
00691 
00692 // A handy wrapper for AddRef.
00693 #define GTEST_ADD_REF_(T) typename ::std::tr1::gtest_internal::AddRef<T>::type
00694

01049   tuple(const tuple& t) : f0_(t.f0_), f1_(t.f1_), f2_(t.f2_), f3_(t.f3_),
01050       f4_(t.f4_), f5_(t.f5_), f6_(t.f6_), f7_(t.f7_) {}
01051

01054       f3_(t.f3_), f4_(t.f4_), f5_(t.f5_), f6_(t.f6_), f7_(t.f7_) {}
01055 
01056   tuple& operator=(const tuple& t) { return CopyFrom(t); }

01061   }

01071     f4_ = t.f4_;
01072     f5_ = t.f5_;
01073     f6_ = t.f6_;
01074     f7_ = t.f7_;
01075     return *this;
01076   }

01307       k < (tuple_size<Tuple>::value), k, Tuple>::type type;

01449 
01450 // 6.1.3.5 Relational operators
01451 
01452 // We only implement == and !=, as we don't have a need for the rest yet.
01453 
01454 namespace gtest_internal {
01455 
01456 // SameSizeTuplePrefixComparator<k, k>::Eq(t1, t2) returns true if the
01457 // first k fields of t1 equals the first k fields of t2.
01458 // SameSizeTuplePrefixComparator(k1, k2) would be a compiler error if
01459 // k1 != k2.
01460 template <int kSize1, int kSize2>
01461 struct SameSizeTuplePrefixComparator;
01462 
01463 template <>
01464 struct SameSizeTuplePrefixComparator<0, 0> {
01465   template <class Tuple1, class Tuple2>
01466   static bool Eq(const Tuple1& /* t1 */, const Tuple2& /* t2 */) {
01467     return true;
01468   }
01469 };
01470 
01471 template <int k>
01472 struct SameSizeTuplePrefixComparator<k, k> {
01473   template <class Tuple1, class Tuple2>
01474   static bool Eq(const Tuple1& t1, const Tuple2& t2) {
01475     return SameSizeTuplePrefixComparator<k - 1, k - 1>::Eq(t1, t2) &&
01476         ::std::tr1::get<k - 1>(t1) == ::std::tr1::get<k - 1>(t2);
01477   }
01478 };
01479 
01480 }  // namespace gtest_internal
01481 
01482 template <GTEST_10_TYPENAMES_(T), GTEST_10_TYPENAMES_(U)>
01483 inline bool operator==(const GTEST_10_TUPLE_(T)& t,
01484                        const GTEST_10_TUPLE_(U)& u) {
01485   return gtest_internal::SameSizeTuplePrefixComparator<
01486       tuple_size<GTEST_10_TUPLE_(T)>::value,
01487       tuple_size<GTEST_10_TUPLE_(U)>::value>::Eq(t, u);
01488 }
01489 
01490 template <GTEST_10_TYPENAMES_(T), GTEST_10_TYPENAMES_(U)>
01491 inline bool operator!=(const GTEST_10_TUPLE_(T)& t,
01492                        const GTEST_10_TUPLE_(U)& u) { return !(t == u); }
01493 
01494 // 6.1.4 Pairs.
01495 // Unimplemented.
01496 
01497 }  // namespace tr1
01498 }  // namespace std

01528 
01529 #endif  // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_TUPLE_H_
01530 # elif GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
01531 
01532 // On Symbian, BOOST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE causes Boost's TR1 tuple library to
01533 // use STLport's tuple implementation, which unfortunately doesn't
01534 // work as the copy of STLport distributed with Symbian is incomplete.
01535 // By making sure BOOST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE is undefined, we force Boost to
01536 // use its own tuple implementation.
01537 #  ifdef BOOST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE
01538 #   undef BOOST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE
01539 #  endif  // BOOST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE
01540 
01541 // This prevents <boost/tr1/detail/config.hpp>, which defines
01542 // BOOST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE, from being #included by Boost's <tuple>.
01543 #  define BOOST_TR1_DETAIL_CONFIG_HPP_INCLUDED
01544 #  include <tuple>
01545 
01546 # elif defined(__GNUC__) && (GTEST_GCC_VER_ >= 40000)
01547 // GCC 4.0+ implements tr1/tuple in the <tr1/tuple> header.  This does
01548 // not conform to the TR1 spec, which requires the header to be <tuple>.
01549 
01550 #  if !GTEST_HAS_RTTI && GTEST_GCC_VER_ < 40302
01551 // Until version 4.3.2, gcc has a bug that causes <tr1/functional>,
01552 // which is #included by <tr1/tuple>, to not compile when RTTI is
01553 // disabled.  _TR1_FUNCTIONAL is the header guard for
01554 // <tr1/functional>.  Hence the following #define is a hack to prevent
01555 // <tr1/functional> from being included.
01556 #   define _TR1_FUNCTIONAL 1
01557 #   include <tr1/tuple>
01558 #   undef _TR1_FUNCTIONAL  // Allows the user to #include
01559                         // <tr1/functional> if he chooses to.
01560 #  else
01561 #   include <tr1/tuple>  // NOLINT

01644 // The GNU compiler emits a warning if nested "if" statements are followed by
01645 // an "else" statement and braces are not used to explicitly disambiguate the
01646 // "else" binding.  This leads to problems with code like:
01647 //
01648 //   if (gate)
01649 //     ASSERT_*(condition) << "Some message";
01650 //
01651 // The "switch (0) case 0:" idiom is used to suppress this.
01652 #ifdef __INTEL_COMPILER
01653 # define GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_
01654 #else
01655 # define GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ switch (0) case 0: default:  // NOLINT
01656 #endif

01658 // Use this annotation at the end of a struct/class definition to
01659 // prevent the compiler from optimizing away instances that are never
01660 // used.  This is useful when all interesting logic happens inside the
01661 // c'tor and / or d'tor.  Example:

01668 // compiler the variable/parameter does not have to be used.
01669 #if defined(__GNUC__) && !defined(COMPILER_ICC)
01670 # define GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ __attribute__ ((unused))
01671 #else
01672 # define GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_
01673 #endif

01742 // The GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_ macro can be used to verify that a compile time
01743 // expression is true. For example, you could use it to verify the
01744 // size of a static array:
01745 //
01746 //   GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_(ARRAYSIZE(content_type_names) == CONTENT_NUM_TYPES,
01747 //                         content_type_names_incorrect_size);
01748 //
01749 // or to make sure a struct is smaller than a certain size:
01750 //
01751 //   GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_(sizeof(foo) < 128, foo_too_large);
01752 //
01753 // The second argument to the macro is the name of the variable. If
01754 // the expression is false, most compilers will issue a warning/error
01755 // containing the name of the variable.
01756 
01757 template <bool>
01758 struct CompileAssert {
01759 };
01760 
01761 #define GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_(expr, msg) \
01762   typedef ::testing::internal::CompileAssert<(bool(expr))> \
01763       msg[bool(expr) ? 1 : -1]
01764 
01765 // Implementation details of GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_:
01766 //
01767 // - GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_ works by defining an array type that has -1
01768 //   elements (and thus is invalid) when the expression is false.
01769 //
01770 // - The simpler definition
01771 //
01772 //    #define GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_(expr, msg) typedef char msg[(expr) ? 1 : -1]
01773 //
01774 //   does not work, as gcc supports variable-length arrays whose sizes
01775 //   are determined at run-time (this is gcc's extension and not part
01776 //   of the C++ standard).  As a result, gcc fails to reject the
01777 //   following code with the simple definition:
01778 //
01779 //     int foo;
01780 //     GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_(foo, msg); // not supposed to compile as foo is
01781 //                                      // not a compile-time constant.
01782 //
01783 // - By using the type CompileAssert<(bool(expr))>, we ensures that
01784 //   expr is a compile-time constant.  (Template arguments must be
01785 //   determined at compile-time.)
01786 //
01787 // - The outter parentheses in CompileAssert<(bool(expr))> are necessary
01788 //   to work around a bug in gcc 3.4.4 and 4.0.1.  If we had written
01789 //
01790 //     CompileAssert<bool(expr)>
01791 //
01792 //   instead, these compilers will refuse to compile
01793 //
01794 //     GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_(5 > 0, some_message);
01795 //
01796 //   (They seem to think the ">" in "5 > 0" marks the end of the
01797 //   template argument list.)
01798 //
01799 // - The array size is (bool(expr) ? 1 : -1), instead of simply
01800 //
01801 //     ((expr) ? 1 : -1).
01802 //
01803 //   This is to avoid running into a bug in MS VC 7.1, which
01804 //   causes ((0.0) ? 1 : -1) to incorrectly evaluate to 1.
01805 
01806 // StaticAssertTypeEqHelper is used by StaticAssertTypeEq defined in gtest.h.
01807 //
01808 // This template is declared, but intentionally undefined.
01809 template <typename T1, typename T2>
01810 struct StaticAssertTypeEqHelper;
01811 
01812 template <typename T>
01813 struct StaticAssertTypeEqHelper<T, T> {};
01814 
01815 #if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
01816 typedef ::string string;
01817 #else
01818 typedef ::std::string string;
01819 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
01820 
01821 #if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
01822 typedef ::wstring wstring;
01823 #elif GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
01824 typedef ::std::wstring wstring;
01825 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING

01827 // A helper for suppressing warnings on constant condition.  It just

01829 GTEST_API_ bool IsTrue(bool condition);

01831 // Defines scoped_ptr.
01832 
01833 // This implementation of scoped_ptr is PARTIAL - it only contains
01834 // enough stuff to satisfy Google Test's need.
01835 template <typename T>
01836 class scoped_ptr {
01837  public:
01838   typedef T element_type;
01839 
01840   explicit scoped_ptr(T* p = NULL) : ptr_(p) {}
01841   ~scoped_ptr() { reset(); }
01842 
01843   T& operator*() const { return *ptr_; }
01844   T* operator->() const { return ptr_; }
01845   T* get() const { return ptr_; }
01846 
01847   T* release() {
01848     T* const ptr = ptr_;
01849     ptr_ = NULL;
01850     return ptr;
01851   }
01852 
01853   void reset(T* p = NULL) {
01854     if (p != ptr_) {
01855       if (IsTrue(sizeof(T) > 0)) {  // Makes sure T is a complete type.
01856         delete ptr_;
01857       }
01858       ptr_ = p;
01859     }
01860   }
01861  private:
01862   T* ptr_;
01863 
01864   GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(scoped_ptr);
01865 };

01867 // Defines RE.
01868 
01869 // A simple C++ wrapper for <regex.h>.  It uses the POSIX Extended
01870 // Regular Expression syntax.
01871 class GTEST_API_ RE {
01872  public:
01873   // A copy constructor is required by the Standard to initialize object
01874   // references from r-values.
01875   RE(const RE& other) { Init(other.pattern()); }
01876 
01877   // Constructs an RE from a string.
01878   RE(const ::std::string& regex) { Init(regex.c_str()); }  // NOLINT
01879 
01880 #if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
01881 
01882   RE(const ::string& regex) { Init(regex.c_str()); }  // NOLINT
01883 
01884 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
01885 
01886   RE(const char* regex) { Init(regex); }  // NOLINT
01887   ~RE();
01888 
01889   // Returns the string representation of the regex.
01890   const char* pattern() const { return pattern_; }
01891 
01892   // FullMatch(str, re) returns true iff regular expression re matches
01893   // the entire str.
01894   // PartialMatch(str, re) returns true iff regular expression re
01895   // matches a substring of str (including str itself).
01896   //
01897   // TODO(wan@google.com): make FullMatch() and PartialMatch() work
01898   // when str contains NUL characters.
01899   static bool FullMatch(const ::std::string& str, const RE& re) {
01900     return FullMatch(str.c_str(), re);
01901   }
01902   static bool PartialMatch(const ::std::string& str, const RE& re) {
01903     return PartialMatch(str.c_str(), re);
01904   }
01905 
01906 #if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
01907 
01908   static bool FullMatch(const ::string& str, const RE& re) {
01909     return FullMatch(str.c_str(), re);
01910   }
01911   static bool PartialMatch(const ::string& str, const RE& re) {
01912     return PartialMatch(str.c_str(), re);
01913   }
01914 
01915 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
01916 
01917   static bool FullMatch(const char* str, const RE& re);
01918   static bool PartialMatch(const char* str, const RE& re);
01919 
01920  private:
01921   void Init(const char* regex);
01922 
01923   // We use a const char* instead of a string, as Google Test may be used
01924   // where string is not available.  We also do not use Google Test's own
01925   // String type here, in order to simplify dependencies between the
01926   // files.
01927   const char* pattern_;
01928   bool is_valid_;
01929 
01930 #if GTEST_USES_POSIX_RE
01931 
01932   regex_t full_regex_;     // For FullMatch().
01933   regex_t partial_regex_;  // For PartialMatch().
01934 
01935 #else  // GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE
01936 
01937   const char* full_pattern_;  // For FullMatch();
01938 
01939 #endif
01940 
01941   GTEST_DISALLOW_ASSIGN_(RE);
01942 };

01992 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE.
01993 //
01994 // GTEST_CHECK_ is an all-mode assert. It aborts the program if the condition
01995 // is not satisfied.
01996 //  Synopsys:
01997 //    GTEST_CHECK_(boolean_condition);
01998 //     or
01999 //    GTEST_CHECK_(boolean_condition) << "Additional message";
02000 //
02001 //    This checks the condition and if the condition is not satisfied
02002 //    it prints message about the condition violation, including the
02003 //    condition itself, plus additional message streamed into it, if any,
02004 //    and then it aborts the program. It aborts the program irrespective of
02005 //    whether it is built in the debug mode or not.
02006 #define GTEST_CHECK_(condition) \
02007     GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
02008     if (::testing::internal::IsTrue(condition)) \
02009       ; \
02010     else \
02011       GTEST_LOG_(FATAL) << "Condition " #condition " failed. "
02012 
02013 // An all-mode assert to verify that the given POSIX-style function
02014 // call returns 0 (indicating success).  Known limitation: this
02015 // doesn't expand to a balanced 'if' statement, so enclose the macro
02016 // in {} if you need to use it as the only statement in an 'if'
02017 // branch.
02018 #define GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(posix_call) \
02019   if (const int gtest_error = (posix_call)) \
02020     GTEST_LOG_(FATAL) << #posix_call << "failed with error " \
02021                       << gtest_error
02022 
02023 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
02024 //
02025 // Use ImplicitCast_ as a safe version of static_cast for upcasting in
02026 // the type hierarchy (e.g. casting a Foo* to a SuperclassOfFoo* or a
02027 // const Foo*).  When you use ImplicitCast_, the compiler checks that
02028 // the cast is safe.  Such explicit ImplicitCast_s are necessary in
02029 // surprisingly many situations where C++ demands an exact type match
02030 // instead of an argument type convertable to a target type.
02031 //
02032 // The syntax for using ImplicitCast_ is the same as for static_cast:
02033 //
02034 //   ImplicitCast_<ToType>(expr)
02035 //
02036 // ImplicitCast_ would have been part of the C++ standard library,
02037 // but the proposal was submitted too late.  It will probably make
02038 // its way into the language in the future.
02039 //
02040 // This relatively ugly name is intentional. It prevents clashes with
02041 // similar functions users may have (e.g., implicit_cast). The internal
02042 // namespace alone is not enough because the function can be found by ADL.
02043 template<typename To>
02044 inline To ImplicitCast_(To x) { return x; }
02045 
02046 // When you upcast (that is, cast a pointer from type Foo to type
02047 // SuperclassOfFoo), it's fine to use ImplicitCast_<>, since upcasts
02048 // always succeed.  When you downcast (that is, cast a pointer from
02049 // type Foo to type SubclassOfFoo), static_cast<> isn't safe, because
02050 // how do you know the pointer is really of type SubclassOfFoo?  It
02051 // could be a bare Foo, or of type DifferentSubclassOfFoo.  Thus,
02052 // when you downcast, you should use this macro.  In debug mode, we
02053 // use dynamic_cast<> to double-check the downcast is legal (we die
02054 // if it's not).  In normal mode, we do the efficient static_cast<>
02055 // instead.  Thus, it's important to test in debug mode to make sure
02056 // the cast is legal!
02057 //    This is the only place in the code we should use dynamic_cast<>.
02058 // In particular, you SHOULDN'T be using dynamic_cast<> in order to
02059 // do RTTI (eg code like this:
02060 //    if (dynamic_cast<Subclass1>(foo)) HandleASubclass1Object(foo);
02061 //    if (dynamic_cast<Subclass2>(foo)) HandleASubclass2Object(foo);
02062 // You should design the code some other way not to need this.
02063 //
02064 // This relatively ugly name is intentional. It prevents clashes with
02065 // similar functions users may have (e.g., down_cast). The internal
02066 // namespace alone is not enough because the function can be found by ADL.
02067 template<typename To, typename From>  // use like this: DownCast_<T*>(foo);
02068 inline To DownCast_(From* f) {  // so we only accept pointers
02069   // Ensures that To is a sub-type of From *.  This test is here only
02070   // for compile-time type checking, and has no overhead in an
02071   // optimized build at run-time, as it will be optimized away
02072   // completely.
02073   if (false) {
02074     const To to = NULL;
02075     ::testing::internal::ImplicitCast_<From*>(to);
02076   }
02077 
02078 #if GTEST_HAS_RTTI
02079   // RTTI: debug mode only!
02080   GTEST_CHECK_(f == NULL || dynamic_cast<To>(f) != NULL);
02081 #endif
02082   return static_cast<To>(f);
02083 }
02084 
02085 // Downcasts the pointer of type Base to Derived.
02086 // Derived must be a subclass of Base. The parameter MUST
02087 // point to a class of type Derived, not any subclass of it.
02088 // When RTTI is available, the function performs a runtime
02089 // check to enforce this.
02090 template <class Derived, class Base>
02091 Derived* CheckedDowncastToActualType(Base* base) {
02092 #if GTEST_HAS_RTTI
02093   GTEST_CHECK_(typeid(*base) == typeid(Derived));
02094   return dynamic_cast<Derived*>(base);  // NOLINT
02095 #else
02096   return static_cast<Derived*>(base);  // Poor man's downcast.
02097 #endif
02098 }

02101

02104 //   GetCapturedStdout - stops capturing stdout and returns the captured string.
02105 //   CaptureStderr     - starts capturing stderr.
02106 //   GetCapturedStderr - stops capturing stderr and returns the captured string.
02107 //
02108 GTEST_API_ void CaptureStdout();
02109 GTEST_API_ String GetCapturedStdout();
02110 GTEST_API_ void CaptureStderr();
02111 GTEST_API_ String GetCapturedStderr();

02126 // Defines synchronization primitives.

02130 // Sleeps for (roughly) n milli-seconds.  This function is only for
02131 // testing Google Test's own constructs.  Don't use it in user tests,
02132 // either directly or indirectly.
02133 inline void SleepMilliseconds(int n) {
02134   const timespec time = {
02135     0,                  // 0 seconds.
02136     n * 1000L * 1000L,  // And n ms.
02137   };
02138   nanosleep(&time, NULL);
02139 }
02140 
02141 // Allows a controller thread to pause execution of newly created
02142 // threads until notified.  Instances of this class must be created
02143 // and destroyed in the controller thread.
02144 //
02145 // This class is only for testing Google Test's own constructs. Do not
02146 // use it in user tests, either directly or indirectly.
02147 class Notification {
02148  public:
02149   Notification() : notified_(false) {}
02150 
02151   // Notifies all threads created with this notification to start. Must
02152   // be called from the controller thread.
02153   void Notify() { notified_ = true; }
02154 
02155   // Blocks until the controller thread notifies. Must be called from a test
02156   // thread.
02157   void WaitForNotification() {
02158     while(!notified_) {
02159       SleepMilliseconds(10);
02160     }
02161   }
02162 
02163  private:
02164   volatile bool notified_;
02165 
02166   GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(Notification);
02167 };
02168 
02169 // As a C-function, ThreadFuncWithCLinkage cannot be templated itself.
02170 // Consequently, it cannot select a correct instantiation of ThreadWithParam
02171 // in order to call its Run(). Introducing ThreadWithParamBase as a
02172 // non-templated base class for ThreadWithParam allows us to bypass this
02173 // problem.
02174 class ThreadWithParamBase {
02175  public:
02176   virtual ~ThreadWithParamBase() {}
02177   virtual void Run() = 0;
02178 };
02179 
02180 // pthread_create() accepts a pointer to a function type with the C linkage.
02181 // According to the Standard (7.5/1), function types with different linkages
02182 // are different even if they are otherwise identical.  Some compilers (for
02183 // example, SunStudio) treat them as different types.  Since class methods
02184 // cannot be defined with C-linkage we need to define a free C-function to
02185 // pass into pthread_create().
02186 extern "C" inline void* ThreadFuncWithCLinkage(void* thread) {
02187   static_cast<ThreadWithParamBase*>(thread)->Run();
02188   return NULL;
02189 }
02190 
02191 // Helper class for testing Google Test's multi-threading constructs.
02192 // To use it, write:
02193 //
02194 //   void ThreadFunc(int param) { /* Do things with param */ }
02195 //   Notification thread_can_start;
02196 //   ...
02197 //   // The thread_can_start parameter is optional; you can supply NULL.
02198 //   ThreadWithParam<int> thread(&ThreadFunc, 5, &thread_can_start);
02199 //   thread_can_start.Notify();
02200 //
02201 // These classes are only for testing Google Test's own constructs. Do
02202 // not use them in user tests, either directly or indirectly.
02203 template <typename T>
02204 class ThreadWithParam : public ThreadWithParamBase {
02205  public:
02206   typedef void (*UserThreadFunc)(T);
02207 
02208   ThreadWithParam(
02209       UserThreadFunc func, T param, Notification* thread_can_start)
02210       : func_(func),
02211         param_(param),
02212         thread_can_start_(thread_can_start),
02213         finished_(false) {
02214     ThreadWithParamBase* const base = this;
02215     // The thread can be created only after all fields except thread_
02216     // have been initialized.
02217     GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(
02218         pthread_create(&thread_, 0, &ThreadFuncWithCLinkage, base));
02219   }
02220   ~ThreadWithParam() { Join(); }
02221 
02222   void Join() {
02223     if (!finished_) {
02224       GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_join(thread_, 0));
02225       finished_ = true;
02226     }
02227   }
02228 
02229   virtual void Run() {
02230     if (thread_can_start_ != NULL)
02231       thread_can_start_->WaitForNotification();
02232     func_(param_);
02233   }
02234 
02235  private:
02236   const UserThreadFunc func_;  // User-supplied thread function.
02237   const T param_;  // User-supplied parameter to the thread function.
02238   // When non-NULL, used to block execution until the controller thread
02239   // notifies.
02240   Notification* const thread_can_start_;
02241   bool finished_;  // true iff we know that the thread function has finished.
02242   pthread_t thread_;  // The native thread object.
02243 
02244   GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ThreadWithParam);
02245 };
02246 
02247 // MutexBase and Mutex implement mutex on pthreads-based platforms. They
02248 // are used in conjunction with class MutexLock:
02249 //
02250 //   Mutex mutex;
02251 //   ...
02252 //   MutexLock lock(&mutex);  // Acquires the mutex and releases it at the end
02253 //                            // of the current scope.
02254 //
02255 // MutexBase implements behavior for both statically and dynamically
02256 // allocated mutexes.  Do not use MutexBase directly.  Instead, write
02257 // the following to define a static mutex:
02258 //
02259 //   GTEST_DEFINE_STATIC_MUTEX_(g_some_mutex);
02260 //
02261 // You can forward declare a static mutex like this:
02262 //
02263 //   GTEST_DECLARE_STATIC_MUTEX_(g_some_mutex);
02264 //
02265 // To create a dynamic mutex, just define an object of type Mutex.
02266 class MutexBase {
02267  public:
02268   // Acquires this mutex.
02269   void Lock() {
02270     GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_lock(&mutex_));
02271     owner_ = pthread_self();
02272   }
02273 
02274   // Releases this mutex.
02275   void Unlock() {
02276     // We don't protect writing to owner_ here, as it's the caller's
02277     // responsibility to ensure that the current thread holds the
02278     // mutex when this is called.
02279     owner_ = 0;
02280     GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_unlock(&mutex_));
02281   }
02282 
02283   // Does nothing if the current thread holds the mutex. Otherwise, crashes
02284   // with high probability.
02285   void AssertHeld() const {
02286     GTEST_CHECK_(owner_ == pthread_self())
02287         << "The current thread is not holding the mutex @" << this;
02288   }
02289 
02290   // A static mutex may be used before main() is entered.  It may even
02291   // be used before the dynamic initialization stage.  Therefore we
02292   // must be able to initialize a static mutex object at link time.
02293   // This means MutexBase has to be a POD and its member variables
02294   // have to be public.
02295  public:
02296   pthread_mutex_t mutex_;  // The underlying pthread mutex.
02297   pthread_t owner_;  // The thread holding the mutex; 0 means no one holds it.
02298 };
02299 
02300 // Forward-declares a static mutex.
02301 # define GTEST_DECLARE_STATIC_MUTEX_(mutex) \
02302     extern ::testing::internal::MutexBase mutex
02303 
02304 // Defines and statically (i.e. at link time) initializes a static mutex.
02305 # define GTEST_DEFINE_STATIC_MUTEX_(mutex) \
02306     ::testing::internal::MutexBase mutex = { PTHREAD_MUTEX_INITIALIZER, 0 }
02307 
02308 // The Mutex class can only be used for mutexes created at runtime. It
02309 // shares its API with MutexBase otherwise.
02310 class Mutex : public MutexBase {
02311  public:
02312   Mutex() {
02313     GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_init(&mutex_, NULL));
02314     owner_ = 0;
02315   }
02316   ~Mutex() {
02317     GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_destroy(&mutex_));
02318   }
02319 
02320  private:
02321   GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(Mutex);
02322 };
02323 
02324 // We cannot name this class MutexLock as the ctor declaration would
02325 // conflict with a macro named MutexLock, which is defined on some
02326 // platforms.  Hence the typedef trick below.
02327 class GTestMutexLock {
02328  public:
02329   explicit GTestMutexLock(MutexBase* mutex)
02330       : mutex_(mutex) { mutex_->Lock(); }
02331 
02332   ~GTestMutexLock() { mutex_->Unlock(); }
02333 
02334  private:
02335   MutexBase* const mutex_;
02336 
02337   GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(GTestMutexLock);
02338 };
02339 
02340 typedef GTestMutexLock MutexLock;
02341 
02342 // Helpers for ThreadLocal.
02343 
02344 // pthread_key_create() requires DeleteThreadLocalValue() to have
02345 // C-linkage.  Therefore it cannot be templatized to access
02346 // ThreadLocal<T>.  Hence the need for class
02347 // ThreadLocalValueHolderBase.
02348 class ThreadLocalValueHolderBase {
02349  public:
02350   virtual ~ThreadLocalValueHolderBase() {}
02351 };
02352 
02353 // Called by pthread to delete thread-local data stored by
02354 // pthread_setspecific().
02355 extern "C" inline void DeleteThreadLocalValue(void* value_holder) {
02356   delete static_cast<ThreadLocalValueHolderBase*>(value_holder);
02357 }
02358 
02359 // Implements thread-local storage on pthreads-based systems.
02360 //
02361 //   // Thread 1
02362 //   ThreadLocal<int> tl(100);  // 100 is the default value for each thread.
02363 //
02364 //   // Thread 2
02365 //   tl.set(150);  // Changes the value for thread 2 only.
02366 //   EXPECT_EQ(150, tl.get());
02367 //
02368 //   // Thread 1
02369 //   EXPECT_EQ(100, tl.get());  // In thread 1, tl has the original value.
02370 //   tl.set(200);
02371 //   EXPECT_EQ(200, tl.get());
02372 //
02373 // The template type argument T must have a public copy constructor.
02374 // In addition, the default ThreadLocal constructor requires T to have
02375 // a public default constructor.
02376 //
02377 // An object managed for a thread by a ThreadLocal instance is deleted
02378 // when the thread exits.  Or, if the ThreadLocal instance dies in
02379 // that thread, when the ThreadLocal dies.  It's the user's
02380 // responsibility to ensure that all other threads using a ThreadLocal
02381 // have exited when it dies, or the per-thread objects for those
02382 // threads will not be deleted.
02383 //
02384 // Google Test only uses global ThreadLocal objects.  That means they
02385 // will die after main() has returned.  Therefore, no per-thread
02386 // object managed by Google Test will be leaked as long as all threads
02387 // using Google Test have exited when main() returns.
02388 template <typename T>
02389 class ThreadLocal {
02390  public:
02391   ThreadLocal() : key_(CreateKey()),
02392                   default_() {}
02393   explicit ThreadLocal(const T& value) : key_(CreateKey()),
02394                                          default_(value) {}
02395 
02396   ~ThreadLocal() {
02397     // Destroys the managed object for the current thread, if any.
02398     DeleteThreadLocalValue(pthread_getspecific(key_));
02399 
02400     // Releases resources associated with the key.  This will *not*
02401     // delete managed objects for other threads.
02402     GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_key_delete(key_));
02403   }
02404 
02405   T* pointer() { return GetOrCreateValue(); }
02406   const T* pointer() const { return GetOrCreateValue(); }
02407   const T& get() const { return *pointer(); }
02408   void set(const T& value) { *pointer() = value; }
02409 
02410  private:
02411   // Holds a value of type T.
02412   class ValueHolder : public ThreadLocalValueHolderBase {
02413    public:
02414     explicit ValueHolder(const T& value) : value_(value) {}
02415 
02416     T* pointer() { return &value_; }
02417 
02418    private:
02419     T value_;
02420     GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ValueHolder);
02421   };
02422 
02423   static pthread_key_t CreateKey() {
02424     pthread_key_t key;
02425     // When a thread exits, DeleteThreadLocalValue() will be called on
02426     // the object managed for that thread.
02427     GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(
02428         pthread_key_create(&key, &DeleteThreadLocalValue));
02429     return key;
02430   }
02431 
02432   T* GetOrCreateValue() const {
02433     ThreadLocalValueHolderBase* const holder =
02434         static_cast<ThreadLocalValueHolderBase*>(pthread_getspecific(key_));
02435     if (holder != NULL) {
02436       return CheckedDowncastToActualType<ValueHolder>(holder)->pointer();
02437     }
02438 
02439     ValueHolder* const new_holder = new ValueHolder(default_);
02440     ThreadLocalValueHolderBase* const holder_base = new_holder;
02441     GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_setspecific(key_, holder_base));
02442     return new_holder->pointer();
02443   }
02444 
02445   // A key pthreads uses for looking up per-thread values.
02446   const pthread_key_t key_;
02447   const T default_;  // The default value for each thread.
02448 
02449   GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ThreadLocal);
02450 };
02451 
02452 # define GTEST_IS_THREADSAFE 1
02453 
02454 #else  // GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
02455

02457 // and thread-local variable).  Necessary for compiling Google Test where
02458 // mutex is not supported - using Google Test in multiple threads is not
02459 // supported on such platforms.
02460 
02461 class Mutex {
02462  public:
02463   Mutex() {}
02464   void AssertHeld() const {}
02465 };
02466 
02467 # define GTEST_DECLARE_STATIC_MUTEX_(mutex) \
02468   extern ::testing::internal::Mutex mutex
02469 
02470 # define GTEST_DEFINE_STATIC_MUTEX_(mutex) ::testing::internal::Mutex mutex
02471 
02472 class GTestMutexLock {
02473  public:
02474   explicit GTestMutexLock(Mutex*) {}  // NOLINT
02475 };
02476 
02477 typedef GTestMutexLock MutexLock;

02479 template <typename T>
02480 class ThreadLocal {
02481  public:
02482   ThreadLocal() : value_() {}
02483   explicit ThreadLocal(const T& value) : value_(value) {}
02484   T* pointer() { return &value_; }
02485   const T* pointer() const { return &value_; }
02486   const T& get() const { return value_; }
02487   void set(const T& value) { value_ = value; }
02488  private:
02489   T value_;
02490 };

02502 // Passing non-POD classes through ellipsis (...) crashes the ARM
02503 // compiler and generates a warning in Sun Studio.  The Nokia Symbian
02504 // and the IBM XL C/C++ compiler try to instantiate a copy constructor
02505 // for objects passed through ellipsis (...), failing for uncopyable
02506 // objects.  We define this to ensure that only POD is passed through
02507 // ellipsis on these systems.
02508 #if defined(__SYMBIAN32__) || defined(__IBMCPP__) || defined(__SUNPRO_CC)
02509 // We lose support for NULL detection where the compiler doesn't like
02510 // passing non-POD classes through ellipsis (...).
02511 # define GTEST_ELLIPSIS_NEEDS_POD_ 1
02512 #else
02513 # define GTEST_CAN_COMPARE_NULL 1
02514 #endif

02517 // const T& and const T* in a function template.  These compilers
02518 // _can_ decide between class template specializations for T and T*,
02519 // so a tr1::type_traits-like is_pointer works.
02520 #if defined(__SYMBIAN32__) || defined(__IBMCPP__)
02521 # define GTEST_NEEDS_IS_POINTER_ 1

02526   typedef bool_constant<bool_value> type;
02527   static const bool value = bool_value;
02528 };
02529 template <bool bool_value> const bool bool_constant<bool_value>::value;
02530 
02531 typedef bool_constant<false> false_type;
02532 typedef bool_constant<true> true_type;
02533

02535 struct is_pointer : public false_type {};
02536 
02537 template <typename T>
02538 struct is_pointer<T*> : public true_type {};
02539

02541 struct IteratorTraits {
02542   typedef typename Iterator::value_type value_type;
02543 };
02544

02546 struct IteratorTraits<T*> {
02547   typedef T value_type;

02566 // Utilities for char.
02567 
02568 // isspace(int ch) and friends accept an unsigned char or EOF.  char
02569 // may be signed, depending on the compiler (or compiler flags).
02570 // Therefore we need to cast a char to unsigned char before calling
02571 // isspace(), etc.
02572 
02573 inline bool IsAlpha(char ch) {
02574   return isalpha(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
02575 }
02576 inline bool IsAlNum(char ch) {
02577   return isalnum(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
02578 }
02579 inline bool IsDigit(char ch) {
02580   return isdigit(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
02581 }
02582 inline bool IsLower(char ch) {
02583   return islower(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
02584 }
02585 inline bool IsSpace(char ch) {
02586   return isspace(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
02587 }
02588 inline bool IsUpper(char ch) {
02589   return isupper(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
02590 }
02591 inline bool IsXDigit(char ch) {
02592   return isxdigit(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
02593 }
02594 
02595 inline char ToLower(char ch) {
02596   return static_cast<char>(tolower(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)));
02597 }
02598 inline char ToUpper(char ch) {
02599   return static_cast<char>(toupper(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)));
02600 }

02703 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
02704   // We are on Windows CE, which has no environment variables.

02707   // Environment variables which we programmatically clear will be set to the
02708   // empty string rather than unset (NULL).  Handle that case.
02709   const char* const env = getenv(name);
02710   return (env != NULL && env[0] != '\0') ? env : NULL;
02711 #else

02731 // The maximum number a BiggestInt can represent.  This definition
02732 // works no matter BiggestInt is represented in one's complement or
02733 // two's complement.
02734 //
02735 // We cannot rely on numeric_limits in STL, as __int64 and long long
02736 // are not part of standard C++ and numeric_limits doesn't need to be
02737 // defined for them.
02738 const BiggestInt kMaxBiggestInt =
02739     ~(static_cast<BiggestInt>(1) << (8*sizeof(BiggestInt) - 1));
02740 
02741 // This template class serves as a compile-time function from size to
02742 // type.  It maps a size in bytes to a primitive type with that
02743 // size. e.g.
02744 //
02745 //   TypeWithSize<4>::UInt
02746 //
02747 // is typedef-ed to be unsigned int (unsigned integer made up of 4
02748 // bytes).
02749 //
02750 // Such functionality should belong to STL, but I cannot find it
02751 // there.
02752 //
02753 // Google Test uses this class in the implementation of floating-point
02754 // comparison.
02755 //
02756 // For now it only handles UInt (unsigned int) as that's all Google Test
02757 // needs.  Other types can be easily added in the future if need
02758 // arises.
02759 template <size_t size>
02760 class TypeWithSize {
02761  public:
02762   // This prevents the user from using TypeWithSize<N> with incorrect
02763   // values of N.
02764   typedef void UInt;
02765 };
02766 
02767 // The specialization for size 4.
02768 template <>
02769 class TypeWithSize<4> {
02770  public:
02771   // unsigned int has size 4 in both gcc and MSVC.
02772   //
02773   // As base/basictypes.h doesn't compile on Windows, we cannot use
02774   // uint32, uint64, and etc here.
02775   typedef int Int;
02776   typedef unsigned int UInt;
02777 };
02778 
02779 // The specialization for size 8.
02780 template <>
02781 class TypeWithSize<8> {
02782  public:
02783 
02784 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
02785   typedef __int64 Int;
02786   typedef unsigned __int64 UInt;
02787 #else
02788   typedef long long Int;  // NOLINT
02789   typedef unsigned long long UInt;  // NOLINT
02790 #endif  // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
02791 };
02792 
02793 // Integer types of known sizes.
02794 typedef TypeWithSize<4>::Int Int32;
02795 typedef TypeWithSize<4>::UInt UInt32;
02796 typedef TypeWithSize<8>::Int Int64;
02797 typedef TypeWithSize<8>::UInt UInt64;
02798 typedef TypeWithSize<8>::Int TimeInMillis;  // Represents time in milliseconds.
02799 
02800 // Utilities for command line flags and environment variables.
02801 
02802 // Macro for referencing flags.
02803 #define GTEST_FLAG(name) FLAGS_gtest_##name
02804 
02805 // Macros for declaring flags.
02806 #define GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(name) GTEST_API_ extern bool GTEST_FLAG(name)
02807 #define GTEST_DECLARE_int32_(name) \
02808     GTEST_API_ extern ::testing::internal::Int32 GTEST_FLAG(name)
02809 #define GTEST_DECLARE_string_(name) \
02810     GTEST_API_ extern ::testing::internal::String GTEST_FLAG(name)
02811 
02812 // Macros for defining flags.
02813 #define GTEST_DEFINE_bool_(name, default_val, doc) \
02814     GTEST_API_ bool GTEST_FLAG(name) = (default_val)
02815 #define GTEST_DEFINE_int32_(name, default_val, doc) \
02816     GTEST_API_ ::testing::internal::Int32 GTEST_FLAG(name) = (default_val)
02817 #define GTEST_DEFINE_string_(name, default_val, doc) \
02818     GTEST_API_ ::testing::internal::String GTEST_FLAG(name) = (default_val)
02819 
02820 // Parses 'str' for a 32-bit signed integer.  If successful, writes the result
02821 // to *value and returns true; otherwise leaves *value unchanged and returns
02822 // false.
02823 // TODO(chandlerc): Find a better way to refactor flag and environment parsing
02824 // out of both gtest-port.cc and gtest.cc to avoid exporting this utility
02825 // function.
02826 bool ParseInt32(const Message& src_text, const char* str, Int32* value);
02827 
02828 // Parses a bool/Int32/string from the environment variable
02829 // corresponding to the given Google Test flag.
02830 bool BoolFromGTestEnv(const char* flag, bool default_val);
02831 GTEST_API_ Int32 Int32FromGTestEnv(const char* flag, Int32 default_val);
02832 const char* StringFromGTestEnv(const char* flag, const char* default_val);

02907 // String - a UTF-8 string class.
02908 //
02909 // For historic reasons, we don't use std::string.
02910 //
02911 // TODO(wan@google.com): replace this class with std::string or
02912 // implement it in terms of the latter.
02913 //
02914 // Note that String can represent both NULL and the empty string,
02915 // while std::string cannot represent NULL.
02916 //
02917 // NULL and the empty string are considered different.  NULL is less
02918 // than anything (including the empty string) except itself.
02919 //
02920 // This class only provides minimum functionality necessary for
02921 // implementing Google Test.  We do not intend to implement a full-fledged
02922 // string class here.
02923 //
02924 // Since the purpose of this class is to provide a substitute for
02925 // std::string on platforms where it cannot be used, we define a copy
02926 // constructor and assignment operators such that we don't need
02927 // conditional compilation in a lot of places.
02928 //
02929 // In order to make the representation efficient, the d'tor of String
02930 // is not virtual.  Therefore DO NOT INHERIT FROM String.
02931 class GTEST_API_ String {
02932  public:
02933   // Static utility methods
02934 
02935   // Returns the input enclosed in double quotes if it's not NULL;
02936   // otherwise returns "(null)".  For example, "\"Hello\"" is returned
02937   // for input "Hello".
02938   //
02939   // This is useful for printing a C string in the syntax of a literal.
02940   //
02941   // Known issue: escape sequences are not handled yet.
02942   static String ShowCStringQuoted(const char* c_str);
02943 
02944   // Clones a 0-terminated C string, allocating memory using new.  The
02945   // caller is responsible for deleting the return value using
02946   // delete[].  Returns the cloned string, or NULL if the input is
02947   // NULL.
02948   //
02949   // This is different from strdup() in string.h, which allocates
02950   // memory using malloc().
02951   static const char* CloneCString(const char* c_str);
02952 
02953 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
02954   // Windows CE does not have the 'ANSI' versions of Win32 APIs. To be
02955   // able to pass strings to Win32 APIs on CE we need to convert them
02956   // to 'Unicode', UTF-16.
02957 
02958   // Creates a UTF-16 wide string from the given ANSI string, allocating
02959   // memory using new. The caller is responsible for deleting the return
02960   // value using delete[]. Returns the wide string, or NULL if the
02961   // input is NULL.
02962   //
02963   // The wide string is created using the ANSI codepage (CP_ACP) to
02964   // match the behaviour of the ANSI versions of Win32 calls and the
02965   // C runtime.
02966   static LPCWSTR AnsiToUtf16(const char* c_str);
02967 
02968   // Creates an ANSI string from the given wide string, allocating
02969   // memory using new. The caller is responsible for deleting the return
02970   // value using delete[]. Returns the ANSI string, or NULL if the
02971   // input is NULL.
02972   //
02973   // The returned string is created using the ANSI codepage (CP_ACP) to
02974   // match the behaviour of the ANSI versions of Win32 calls and the
02975   // C runtime.
02976   static const char* Utf16ToAnsi(LPCWSTR utf16_str);
02977 #endif
02978 
02979   // Compares two C strings.  Returns true iff they have the same content.
02980   //
02981   // Unlike strcmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s).  A
02982   // NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL C string,
02983   // including the empty string.
02984   static bool CStringEquals(const char* lhs, const char* rhs);
02985 
02986   // Converts a wide C string to a String using the UTF-8 encoding.
02987   // NULL will be converted to "(null)".  If an error occurred during
02988   // the conversion, "(failed to convert from wide string)" is
02989   // returned.
02990   static String ShowWideCString(const wchar_t* wide_c_str);
02991 
02992   // Similar to ShowWideCString(), except that this function encloses
02993   // the converted string in double quotes.
02994   static String ShowWideCStringQuoted(const wchar_t* wide_c_str);
02995 
02996   // Compares two wide C strings.  Returns true iff they have the same
02997   // content.
02998   //
02999   // Unlike wcscmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s).  A
03000   // NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL C string,
03001   // including the empty string.
03002   static bool WideCStringEquals(const wchar_t* lhs, const wchar_t* rhs);
03003 
03004   // Compares two C strings, ignoring case.  Returns true iff they
03005   // have the same content.
03006   //
03007   // Unlike strcasecmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s).
03008   // A NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL C string,
03009   // including the empty string.
03010   static bool CaseInsensitiveCStringEquals(const char* lhs,
03011                                            const char* rhs);
03012 
03013   // Compares two wide C strings, ignoring case.  Returns true iff they
03014   // have the same content.
03015   //
03016   // Unlike wcscasecmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s).
03017   // A NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL wide C string,
03018   // including the empty string.
03019   // NB: The implementations on different platforms slightly differ.
03020   // On windows, this method uses _wcsicmp which compares according to LC_CTYPE
03021   // environment variable. On GNU platform this method uses wcscasecmp
03022   // which compares according to LC_CTYPE category of the current locale.
03023   // On MacOS X, it uses towlower, which also uses LC_CTYPE category of the
03024   // current locale.
03025   static bool CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(const wchar_t* lhs,
03026                                                const wchar_t* rhs);
03027 
03028   // Formats a list of arguments to a String, using the same format
03029   // spec string as for printf.
03030   //
03031   // We do not use the StringPrintf class as it is not universally
03032   // available.
03033   //
03034   // The result is limited to 4096 characters (including the tailing
03035   // 0).  If 4096 characters are not enough to format the input,
03036   // "<buffer exceeded>" is returned.
03037   static String Format(const char* format, ...);
03038 
03039   // C'tors
03040 
03041   // The default c'tor constructs a NULL string.
03042   String() : c_str_(NULL), length_(0) {}
03043 
03044   // Constructs a String by cloning a 0-terminated C string.
03045   String(const char* a_c_str) {  // NOLINT
03046     if (a_c_str == NULL) {
03047       c_str_ = NULL;
03048       length_ = 0;
03049     } else {
03050       ConstructNonNull(a_c_str, strlen(a_c_str));
03051     }
03052   }
03053 
03054   // Constructs a String by copying a given number of chars from a
03055   // buffer.  E.g. String("hello", 3) creates the string "hel",
03056   // String("a\0bcd", 4) creates "a\0bc", String(NULL, 0) creates "",
03057   // and String(NULL, 1) results in access violation.
03058   String(const char* buffer, size_t a_length) {
03059     ConstructNonNull(buffer, a_length);
03060   }
03061 
03062   // The copy c'tor creates a new copy of the string.  The two
03063   // String objects do not share content.
03064   String(const String& str) : c_str_(NULL), length_(0) { *this = str; }
03065 
03066   // D'tor.  String is intended to be a final class, so the d'tor
03067   // doesn't need to be virtual.
03068   ~String() { delete[] c_str_; }
03069 
03070   // Allows a String to be implicitly converted to an ::std::string or
03071   // ::string, and vice versa.  Converting a String containing a NULL
03072   // pointer to ::std::string or ::string is undefined behavior.
03073   // Converting a ::std::string or ::string containing an embedded NUL
03074   // character to a String will result in the prefix up to the first
03075   // NUL character.
03076   String(const ::std::string& str) {
03077     ConstructNonNull(str.c_str(), str.length());
03078   }
03079 
03080   operator ::std::string() const { return ::std::string(c_str(), length()); }
03081 
03082 #if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
03083   String(const ::string& str) {
03084     ConstructNonNull(str.c_str(), str.length());
03085   }
03086 
03087   operator ::string() const { return ::string(c_str(), length()); }
03088 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
03089 
03090   // Returns true iff this is an empty string (i.e. "").
03091   bool empty() const { return (c_str() != NULL) && (length() == 0); }
03092 
03093   // Compares this with another String.
03094   // Returns < 0 if this is less than rhs, 0 if this is equal to rhs, or > 0
03095   // if this is greater than rhs.
03096   int Compare(const String& rhs) const;
03097 
03098   // Returns true iff this String equals the given C string.  A NULL
03099   // string and a non-NULL string are considered not equal.
03100   bool operator==(const char* a_c_str) const { return Compare(a_c_str) == 0; }
03101 
03102   // Returns true iff this String is less than the given String.  A
03103   // NULL string is considered less than "".
03104   bool operator<(const String& rhs) const { return Compare(rhs) < 0; }
03105 
03106   // Returns true iff this String doesn't equal the given C string.  A NULL
03107   // string and a non-NULL string are considered not equal.
03108   bool operator!=(const char* a_c_str) const { return !(*this == a_c_str); }
03109 
03110   // Returns true iff this String ends with the given suffix.  *Any*
03111   // String is considered to end with a NULL or empty suffix.
03112   bool EndsWith(const char* suffix) const;
03113 
03114   // Returns true iff this String ends with the given suffix, not considering
03115   // case. Any String is considered to end with a NULL or empty suffix.
03116   bool EndsWithCaseInsensitive(const char* suffix) const;
03117 
03118   // Returns the length of the encapsulated string, or 0 if the
03119   // string is NULL.
03120   size_t length() const { return length_; }
03121 
03122   // Gets the 0-terminated C string this String object represents.
03123   // The String object still owns the string.  Therefore the caller
03124   // should NOT delete the return value.
03125   const char* c_str() const { return c_str_; }
03126 
03127   // Assigns a C string to this object.  Self-assignment works.
03128   const String& operator=(const char* a_c_str) {
03129     return *this = String(a_c_str);
03130   }
03131 
03132   // Assigns a String object to this object.  Self-assignment works.
03133   const String& operator=(const String& rhs) {
03134     if (this != &rhs) {
03135       delete[] c_str_;
03136       if (rhs.c_str() == NULL) {
03137         c_str_ = NULL;
03138         length_ = 0;
03139       } else {
03140         ConstructNonNull(rhs.c_str(), rhs.length());
03141       }
03142     }
03143 
03144     return *this;
03145   }
03146 
03147  private:
03148   // Constructs a non-NULL String from the given content.  This
03149   // function can only be called when c_str_ has not been allocated.
03150   // ConstructNonNull(NULL, 0) results in an empty string ("").
03151   // ConstructNonNull(NULL, non_zero) is undefined behavior.
03152   void ConstructNonNull(const char* buffer, size_t a_length) {
03153     char* const str = new char[a_length + 1];
03154     memcpy(str, buffer, a_length);
03155     str[a_length] = '\0';
03156     c_str_ = str;
03157     length_ = a_length;
03158   }
03159 
03160   const char* c_str_;
03161   size_t length_;
03162 };  // class String
03163 
03164 // Streams a String to an ostream.  Each '\0' character in the String
03165 // is replaced with "\\0".
03166 inline ::std::ostream& operator<<(::std::ostream& os, const String& str) {
03167   if (str.c_str() == NULL) {
03168     os << "(null)";
03169   } else {
03170     const char* const c_str = str.c_str();
03171     for (size_t i = 0; i != str.length(); i++) {
03172       if (c_str[i] == '\0') {
03173         os << "\\0";
03174       } else {
03175         os << c_str[i];
03176       }
03177     }
03178   }
03179   return os;
03180 }
03181 
03182 // Gets the content of the stringstream's buffer as a String.  Each '\0'
03183 // character in the buffer is replaced with "\\0".
03184 GTEST_API_ String StringStreamToString(::std::stringstream* stream);
03185 
03186 // Converts a streamable value to a String.  A NULL pointer is
03187 // converted to "(null)".  When the input value is a ::string,
03188 // ::std::string, ::wstring, or ::std::wstring object, each NUL
03189 // character in it is replaced with "\\0".
03190 
03191 // Declared here but defined in gtest.h, so that it has access
03192 // to the definition of the Message class, required by the ARM
03193 // compiler.
03194 template <typename T>
03195 String StreamableToString(const T& streamable);
03196 
03197 }  // namespace internal
03198 }  // namespace testing
