08255 namespace testing {
08256 
08257 // This flag controls the style of death tests.  Valid values are "threadsafe",
08258 // meaning that the death test child process will re-execute the test binary
08259 // from the start, running only a single death test, or "fast",
08260 // meaning that the child process will execute the test logic immediately
08261 // after forking.
08262 GTEST_DECLARE_string_(death_test_style);
08263 
08264 #if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
08265 
08266 // The following macros are useful for writing death tests.
08267 
08268 // Here's what happens when an ASSERT_DEATH* or EXPECT_DEATH* is
08269 // executed:
08270 //
08271 //   1. It generates a warning if there is more than one active
08272 //   thread.  This is because it's safe to fork() or clone() only
08273 //   when there is a single thread.
08274 //
08275 //   2. The parent process clone()s a sub-process and runs the death
08276 //   test in it; the sub-process exits with code 0 at the end of the
08277 //   death test, if it hasn't exited already.
08278 //
08279 //   3. The parent process waits for the sub-process to terminate.
08280 //
08281 //   4. The parent process checks the exit code and error message of
08282 //   the sub-process.
08283 //
08284 // Examples:
08285 //
08286 //   ASSERT_DEATH(server.SendMessage(56, "Hello"), "Invalid port number");
08287 //   for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
08288 //     EXPECT_DEATH(server.ProcessRequest(i),
08289 //                  "Invalid request .* in ProcessRequest()")
08290 //         << "Failed to die on request " << i);
08291 //   }
08292 //
08293 //   ASSERT_EXIT(server.ExitNow(), ::testing::ExitedWithCode(0), "Exiting");
08294 //
08295 //   bool KilledBySIGHUP(int exit_code) {
08296 //     return WIFSIGNALED(exit_code) && WTERMSIG(exit_code) == SIGHUP;
08297 //   }
08298 //
08299 //   ASSERT_EXIT(client.HangUpServer(), KilledBySIGHUP, "Hanging up!");
08300 //
08301 // On the regular expressions used in death tests:
08302 //
08303 //   On POSIX-compliant systems (*nix), we use the <regex.h> library,
08304 //   which uses the POSIX extended regex syntax.
08305 //
08306 //   On other platforms (e.g. Windows), we only support a simple regex
08307 //   syntax implemented as part of Google Test.  This limited
08308 //   implementation should be enough most of the time when writing
08309 //   death tests; though it lacks many features you can find in PCRE
08310 //   or POSIX extended regex syntax.  For example, we don't support
08311 //   union ("x|y"), grouping ("(xy)"), brackets ("[xy]"), and
08312 //   repetition count ("x{5,7}"), among others.
08313 //
08314 //   Below is the syntax that we do support.  We chose it to be a
08315 //   subset of both PCRE and POSIX extended regex, so it's easy to
08316 //   learn wherever you come from.  In the following: 'A' denotes a
08317 //   literal character, period (.), or a single \\ escape sequence;
08318 //   'x' and 'y' denote regular expressions; 'm' and 'n' are for
08319 //   natural numbers.
08320 //
08321 //     c     matches any literal character c
08322 //     \\d   matches any decimal digit
08323 //     \\D   matches any character that's not a decimal digit
08324 //     \\f   matches \f
08325 //     \\n   matches \n
08326 //     \\r   matches \r
08327 //     \\s   matches any ASCII whitespace, including \n
08328 //     \\S   matches any character that's not a whitespace
08329 //     \\t   matches \t
08330 //     \\v   matches \v
08331 //     \\w   matches any letter, _, or decimal digit
08332 //     \\W   matches any character that \\w doesn't match
08333 //     \\c   matches any literal character c, which must be a punctuation
08334 //     .     matches any single character except \n
08335 //     A?    matches 0 or 1 occurrences of A
08336 //     A*    matches 0 or many occurrences of A
08337 //     A+    matches 1 or many occurrences of A
08338 //     ^     matches the beginning of a string (not that of each line)
08339 //     $     matches the end of a string (not that of each line)
08340 //     xy    matches x followed by y
08341 //
08342 //   If you accidentally use PCRE or POSIX extended regex features
08343 //   not implemented by us, you will get a run-time failure.  In that
08344 //   case, please try to rewrite your regular expression within the
08345 //   above syntax.
08346 //
08347 //   This implementation is *not* meant to be as highly tuned or robust
08348 //   as a compiled regex library, but should perform well enough for a
08349 //   death test, which already incurs significant overhead by launching
08350 //   a child process.
08351 //
08352 // Known caveats:
08353 //
08354 //   A "threadsafe" style death test obtains the path to the test
08355 //   program from argv[0] and re-executes it in the sub-process.  For
08356 //   simplicity, the current implementation doesn't search the PATH
08357 //   when launching the sub-process.  This means that the user must
08358 //   invoke the test program via a path that contains at least one
08359 //   path separator (e.g. path/to/foo_test and
08360 //   /absolute/path/to/bar_test are fine, but foo_test is not).  This
08361 //   is rarely a problem as people usually don't put the test binary
08362 //   directory in PATH.
08363 //
08364 // TODO(wan@google.com): make thread-safe death tests search the PATH.
08365 
08366 // Asserts that a given statement causes the program to exit, with an
08367 // integer exit status that satisfies predicate, and emitting error output
08368 // that matches regex.
08369 # define ASSERT_EXIT(statement, predicate, regex) \
08370     GTEST_DEATH_TEST_(statement, predicate, regex, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
08371 
08372 // Like ASSERT_EXIT, but continues on to successive tests in the
08373 // test case, if any:
08374 # define EXPECT_EXIT(statement, predicate, regex) \
08375     GTEST_DEATH_TEST_(statement, predicate, regex, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
08376 
08377 // Asserts that a given statement causes the program to exit, either by
08378 // explicitly exiting with a nonzero exit code or being killed by a
08379 // signal, and emitting error output that matches regex.
08380 # define ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex) \
08381     ASSERT_EXIT(statement, ::testing::internal::ExitedUnsuccessfully, regex)
08382 
08383 // Like ASSERT_DEATH, but continues on to successive tests in the
08384 // test case, if any:
08385 # define EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex) \
08386     EXPECT_EXIT(statement, ::testing::internal::ExitedUnsuccessfully, regex)
08387 
08388 // Two predicate classes that can be used in {ASSERT,EXPECT}_EXIT*:
08389 
08390 // Tests that an exit code describes a normal exit with a given exit code.
08391 class GTEST_API_ ExitedWithCode {
08392  public:
08393   explicit ExitedWithCode(int exit_code);
08394   bool operator()(int exit_status) const;
08395  private:
08396   // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
08397   void operator=(const ExitedWithCode& other);
08398 
08399   const int exit_code_;
08400 };

08414 // EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH asserts that the given statements die in debug mode.
08415 // The death testing framework causes this to have interesting semantics,
08416 // since the sideeffects of the call are only visible in opt mode, and not
08417 // in debug mode.
08418 //
08419 // In practice, this can be used to test functions that utilize the
08420 // LOG(DFATAL) macro using the following style:
08421 //
08422 // int DieInDebugOr12(int* sideeffect) {
08423 //   if (sideeffect) {
08424 //     *sideeffect = 12;
08425 //   }
08426 //   LOG(DFATAL) << "death";
08427 //   return 12;
08428 // }
08429 //
08430 // TEST(TestCase, TestDieOr12WorksInDgbAndOpt) {
08431 //   int sideeffect = 0;
08432 //   // Only asserts in dbg.
08433 //   EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(DieInDebugOr12(&sideeffect), "death");
08434 //
08435 // #ifdef NDEBUG
08436 //   // opt-mode has sideeffect visible.
08437 //   EXPECT_EQ(12, sideeffect);
08438 // #else
08439 //   // dbg-mode no visible sideeffect.
08440 //   EXPECT_EQ(0, sideeffect);
08441 // #endif
08442 // }
08443 //
08444 // This will assert that DieInDebugReturn12InOpt() crashes in debug
08445 // mode, usually due to a DCHECK or LOG(DFATAL), but returns the
08446 // appropriate fallback value (12 in this case) in opt mode. If you
08447 // need to test that a function has appropriate side-effects in opt
08448 // mode, include assertions against the side-effects.  A general
08449 // pattern for this is:
08450 //
08451 // EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH({
08452 //   // Side-effects here will have an effect after this statement in
08453 //   // opt mode, but none in debug mode.
08454 //   EXPECT_EQ(12, DieInDebugOr12(&sideeffect));
08455 // }, "death");
08456 //
08457 # ifdef NDEBUG
08458 
08459 #  define EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
08460   do { statement; } while (::testing::internal::AlwaysFalse())
08461 
08462 #  define ASSERT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
08463   do { statement; } while (::testing::internal::AlwaysFalse())
08464 
08465 # else
08466 
08467 #  define EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
08468   EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex)
08469 
08470 #  define ASSERT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
08471   ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex)
08472 
08473 # endif  // NDEBUG for EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH
08474 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
08475 
08476 // EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) and
08477 // ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) expand to real death tests if
08478 // death tests are supported; otherwise they just issue a warning.  This is
08479 // useful when you are combining death test assertions with normal test
08480 // assertions in one test.
08481 #if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
08482 # define EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
08483     EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex)
08484 # define ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
08485     ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex)
08486 #else
08487 # define EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
08488     GTEST_UNSUPPORTED_DEATH_TEST_(statement, regex, )
08489 # define ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
08490     GTEST_UNSUPPORTED_DEATH_TEST_(statement, regex, return)
08491 #endif
08492 
08493 }  // namespace testing
08494 
08495 #endif  // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_DEATH_TEST_H_

08549 // The Message class works like an ostream repeater.
08550 //
08551 // Typical usage:
08552 //
08553 //   1. You stream a bunch of values to a Message object.
08554 //      It will remember the text in a stringstream.
08555 //   2. Then you stream the Message object to an ostream.
08556 //      This causes the text in the Message to be streamed
08557 //      to the ostream.
08558 //
08559 // For example;
08560 //
08561 //   testing::Message foo;
08562 //   foo << 1 << " != " << 2;
08563 //   std::cout << foo;
08564 //
08565 // will print "1 != 2".
08566 //
08567 // Message is not intended to be inherited from.  In particular, its
08568 // destructor is not virtual.
08569 //
08570 // Note that stringstream behaves differently in gcc and in MSVC.  You
08571 // can stream a NULL char pointer to it in the former, but not in the
08572 // latter (it causes an access violation if you do).  The Message
08573 // class hides this difference by treating a NULL char pointer as
08574 // "(null)".
08575 class GTEST_API_ Message {
08576  private:
08577   // The type of basic IO manipulators (endl, ends, and flush) for
08578   // narrow streams.
08579   typedef std::ostream& (*BasicNarrowIoManip)(std::ostream&);
08580 
08581  public:
08582   // Constructs an empty Message.
08583   // We allocate the stringstream separately because otherwise each use of
08584   // ASSERT/EXPECT in a procedure adds over 200 bytes to the procedure's
08585   // stack frame leading to huge stack frames in some cases; gcc does not reuse
08586   // the stack space.
08587   Message() : ss_(new ::std::stringstream) {
08588     // By default, we want there to be enough precision when printing
08589     // a double to a Message.
08590     *ss_ << std::setprecision(std::numeric_limits<double>::digits10 + 2);
08591   }
08592 
08593   // Copy constructor.
08594   Message(const Message& msg) : ss_(new ::std::stringstream) {  // NOLINT
08595     *ss_ << msg.GetString();
08596   }
08597 
08598   // Constructs a Message from a C-string.
08599   explicit Message(const char* str) : ss_(new ::std::stringstream) {
08600     *ss_ << str;
08601   }
08602 
08603 #if GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
08604   // Streams a value (either a pointer or not) to this object.
08605   template <typename T>
08606   inline Message& operator <<(const T& value) {
08607     StreamHelper(typename internal::is_pointer<T>::type(), value);
08608     return *this;
08609   }
08610 #else
08611   // Streams a non-pointer value to this object.
08612   template <typename T>
08613   inline Message& operator <<(const T& val) {
08614     ::GTestStreamToHelper(ss_.get(), val);
08615     return *this;
08616   }
08617 
08618   // Streams a pointer value to this object.
08619   //
08620   // This function is an overload of the previous one.  When you
08621   // stream a pointer to a Message, this definition will be used as it
08622   // is more specialized.  (The C++ Standard, section
08623   // [temp.func.order].)  If you stream a non-pointer, then the
08624   // previous definition will be used.
08625   //
08626   // The reason for this overload is that streaming a NULL pointer to
08627   // ostream is undefined behavior.  Depending on the compiler, you
08628   // may get "0", "(nil)", "(null)", or an access violation.  To
08629   // ensure consistent result across compilers, we always treat NULL
08630   // as "(null)".
08631   template <typename T>
08632   inline Message& operator <<(T* const& pointer) {  // NOLINT
08633     if (pointer == NULL) {
08634       *ss_ << "(null)";
08635     } else {
08636       ::GTestStreamToHelper(ss_.get(), pointer);
08637     }
08638     return *this;
08639   }
08640 #endif  // GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
08641 
08642   // Since the basic IO manipulators are overloaded for both narrow
08643   // and wide streams, we have to provide this specialized definition
08644   // of operator <<, even though its body is the same as the
08645   // templatized version above.  Without this definition, streaming
08646   // endl or other basic IO manipulators to Message will confuse the
08647   // compiler.
08648   Message& operator <<(BasicNarrowIoManip val) {
08649     *ss_ << val;
08650     return *this;
08651   }
08652 
08653   // Instead of 1/0, we want to see true/false for bool values.
08654   Message& operator <<(bool b) {
08655     return *this << (b ? "true" : "false");
08656   }
08657 
08658   // These two overloads allow streaming a wide C string to a Message
08659   // using the UTF-8 encoding.
08660   Message& operator <<(const wchar_t* wide_c_str) {
08661     return *this << internal::String::ShowWideCString(wide_c_str);
08662   }
08663   Message& operator <<(wchar_t* wide_c_str) {
08664     return *this << internal::String::ShowWideCString(wide_c_str);
08665   }
08666 
08667 #if GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
08668   // Converts the given wide string to a narrow string using the UTF-8
08669   // encoding, and streams the result to this Message object.
08670   Message& operator <<(const ::std::wstring& wstr);
08671 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
08672 
08673 #if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
08674   // Converts the given wide string to a narrow string using the UTF-8
08675   // encoding, and streams the result to this Message object.
08676   Message& operator <<(const ::wstring& wstr);
08677 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
08678 
08679   // Gets the text streamed to this object so far as a String.
08680   // Each '\0' character in the buffer is replaced with "\\0".
08681   //
08682   // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
08683   internal::String GetString() const {
08684     return internal::StringStreamToString(ss_.get());
08685   }
08686 
08687  private:
08688 
08689 #if GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
08690   // These are needed as the Nokia Symbian Compiler cannot decide between
08691   // const T& and const T* in a function template. The Nokia compiler _can_
08692   // decide between class template specializations for T and T*, so a
08693   // tr1::type_traits-like is_pointer works, and we can overload on that.
08694   template <typename T>
08695   inline void StreamHelper(internal::true_type /*dummy*/, T* pointer) {
08696     if (pointer == NULL) {
08697       *ss_ << "(null)";
08698     } else {
08699       ::GTestStreamToHelper(ss_.get(), pointer);
08700     }
08701   }
08702   template <typename T>
08703   inline void StreamHelper(internal::false_type /*dummy*/, const T& value) {
08704     ::GTestStreamToHelper(ss_.get(), value);
08705   }
08706 #endif  // GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN
08707 
08708   // We'll hold the text streamed to this object here.
08709   const internal::scoped_ptr< ::std::stringstream> ss_;
08710 
08711   // We declare (but don't implement) this to prevent the compiler
08712   // from implementing the assignment operator.
08713   void operator=(const Message&);
08714 };
08715 
08716 // Streams a Message to an ostream.
08717 inline std::ostream& operator <<(std::ostream& os, const Message& sb) {
08718   return os << sb.GetString();
08719 }
08720 
08721 }  // namespace testing
08722 
08723 #endif  // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_MESSAGE_H_

08768 // Value-parameterized tests allow you to test your code with different
08769 // parameters without writing multiple copies of the same test.
08770 //
08771 // Here is how you use value-parameterized tests:
08772 
08773 #if 0
08774 
08775 // To write value-parameterized tests, first you should define a fixture
08776 // class. It is usually derived from testing::TestWithParam<T> (see below for
08777 // another inheritance scheme that's sometimes useful in more complicated
08778 // class hierarchies), where the type of your parameter values.
08779 // TestWithParam<T> is itself derived from testing::Test. T can be any
08780 // copyable type. If it's a raw pointer, you are responsible for managing the
08781 // lifespan of the pointed values.
08782 
08783 class FooTest : public ::testing::TestWithParam<const char*> {
08784   // You can implement all the usual class fixture members here.
08785 };
08786 
08787 // Then, use the TEST_P macro to define as many parameterized tests
08788 // for this fixture as you want. The _P suffix is for "parameterized"
08789 // or "pattern", whichever you prefer to think.
08790 
08791 TEST_P(FooTest, DoesBlah) {
08792   // Inside a test, access the test parameter with the GetParam() method
08793   // of the TestWithParam<T> class:
08794   EXPECT_TRUE(foo.Blah(GetParam()));
08795   ...
08796 }
08797 
08798 TEST_P(FooTest, HasBlahBlah) {
08799   ...
08800 }
08801 
08802 // Finally, you can use INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P to instantiate the test
08803 // case with any set of parameters you want. Google Test defines a number
08804 // of functions for generating test parameters. They return what we call
08805 // (surprise!) parameter generators. Here is a  summary of them, which
08806 // are all in the testing namespace:
08807 //
08808 //
08809 //  Range(begin, end [, step]) - Yields values {begin, begin+step,
08810 //                               begin+step+step, ...}. The values do not
08811 //                               include end. step defaults to 1.
08812 //  Values(v1, v2, ..., vN)    - Yields values {v1, v2, ..., vN}.
08813 //  ValuesIn(container)        - Yields values from a C-style array, an STL
08814 //  ValuesIn(begin,end)          container, or an iterator range [begin, end).
08815 //  Bool()                     - Yields sequence {false, true}.
08816 //  Combine(g1, g2, ..., gN)   - Yields all combinations (the Cartesian product
08817 //                               for the math savvy) of the values generated
08818 //                               by the N generators.
08819 //
08820 // For more details, see comments at the definitions of these functions below
08821 // in this file.
08822 //
08823 // The following statement will instantiate tests from the FooTest test case
08824 // each with parameter values "meeny", "miny", and "moe".
08825 
08826 INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(InstantiationName,
08827                         FooTest,
08828                         Values("meeny", "miny", "moe"));
08829 
08830 // To distinguish different instances of the pattern, (yes, you
08831 // can instantiate it more then once) the first argument to the
08832 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P macro is a prefix that will be added to the
08833 // actual test case name. Remember to pick unique prefixes for different
08834 // instantiations. The tests from the instantiation above will have
08835 // these names:
08836 //
08837 //    * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/0 for "meeny"
08838 //    * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/1 for "miny"
08839 //    * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/2 for "moe"
08840 //    * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/0 for "meeny"
08841 //    * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/1 for "miny"
08842 //    * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/2 for "moe"
08843 //
08844 // You can use these names in --gtest_filter.
08845 //
08846 // This statement will instantiate all tests from FooTest again, each
08847 // with parameter values "cat" and "dog":
08848 
08849 const char* pets[] = {"cat", "dog"};
08850 INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(AnotherInstantiationName, FooTest, ValuesIn(pets));
08851 
08852 // The tests from the instantiation above will have these names:
08853 //
08854 //    * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/0 for "cat"
08855 //    * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/1 for "dog"
08856 //    * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/0 for "cat"
08857 //    * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/1 for "dog"
08858 //
08859 // Please note that INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P will instantiate all tests
08860 // in the given test case, whether their definitions come before or
08861 // AFTER the INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P statement.
08862 //
08863 // Please also note that generator expressions (including parameters to the
08864 // generators) are evaluated in InitGoogleTest(), after main() has started.
08865 // This allows the user on one hand, to adjust generator parameters in order
08866 // to dynamically determine a set of tests to run and on the other hand,
08867 // give the user a chance to inspect the generated tests with Google Test
08868 // reflection API before RUN_ALL_TESTS() is executed.
08869 //
08870 // You can see samples/sample7_unittest.cc and samples/sample8_unittest.cc
08871 // for more examples.
08872 //
08873 // In the future, we plan to publish the API for defining new parameter
08874 // generators. But for now this interface remains part of the internal
08875 // implementation and is subject to change.
08876 //
08877 //
08878 // A parameterized test fixture must be derived from testing::Test and from
08879 // testing::WithParamInterface<T>, where T is the type of the parameter
08880 // values. Inheriting from TestWithParam<T> satisfies that requirement because
08881 // TestWithParam<T> inherits from both Test and WithParamInterface. In more
08882 // complicated hierarchies, however, it is occasionally useful to inherit
08883 // separately from Test and WithParamInterface. For example:
08884 
08885 class BaseTest : public ::testing::Test {
08886   // You can inherit all the usual members for a non-parameterized test
08887   // fixture here.
08888 };
08889 
08890 class DerivedTest : public BaseTest, public ::testing::WithParamInterface<int> {
08891   // The usual test fixture members go here too.
08892 };
08893 
08894 TEST_F(BaseTest, HasFoo) {
08895   // This is an ordinary non-parameterized test.
08896 }
08897 
08898 TEST_P(DerivedTest, DoesBlah) {
08899   // GetParam works just the same here as if you inherit from TestWithParam.
08900   EXPECT_TRUE(foo.Blah(GetParam()));
08901 }
08902 
08903 #endif  // 0

08985 // Authors: Dan Egnor (egnor@google.com)
08986 //
08987 // A "smart" pointer type with reference tracking.  Every pointer to a
08988 // particular object is kept on a circular linked list.  When the last pointer
08989 // to an object is destroyed or reassigned, the object is deleted.
08990 //
08991 // Used properly, this deletes the object when the last reference goes away.
08992 // There are several caveats:
08993 // - Like all reference counting schemes, cycles lead to leaks.
08994 // - Each smart pointer is actually two pointers (8 bytes instead of 4).
08995 // - Every time a pointer is assigned, the entire list of pointers to that
08996 //   object is traversed.  This class is therefore NOT SUITABLE when there
08997 //   will often be more than two or three pointers to a particular object.
08998 // - References are only tracked as long as linked_ptr<> objects are copied.
08999 //   If a linked_ptr<> is converted to a raw pointer and back, BAD THINGS
09000 //   will happen (double deletion).
09001 //
09002 // A good use of this class is storing object references in STL containers.
09003 // You can safely put linked_ptr<> in a vector<>.
09004 // Other uses may not be as good.
09005 //
09006 // Note: If you use an incomplete type with linked_ptr<>, the class
09007 // *containing* linked_ptr<> must have a constructor and destructor (even
09008 // if they do nothing!).
09009 //
09010 // Bill Gibbons suggested we use something like this.
09011 //
09012 // Thread Safety:
09013 //   Unlike other linked_ptr implementations, in this implementation
09014 //   a linked_ptr object is thread-safe in the sense that:
09015 //     - it's safe to copy linked_ptr objects concurrently,
09016 //     - it's safe to copy *from* a linked_ptr and read its underlying
09017 //       raw pointer (e.g. via get()) concurrently, and
09018 //     - it's safe to write to two linked_ptrs that point to the same
09019 //       shared object concurrently.
09020 // TODO(wan@google.com): rename this to safe_linked_ptr to avoid
09021 // confusion with normal linked_ptr.
09022 
09023 #ifndef GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_LINKED_PTR_H_
09024 #define GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_LINKED_PTR_H_
09025 
09026 #include <stdlib.h>
09027 #include <assert.h>
09028 
09029 
09030 namespace testing {
09031 namespace internal {
09032 
09033 // Protects copying of all linked_ptr objects.
09034 GTEST_API_ GTEST_DECLARE_STATIC_MUTEX_(g_linked_ptr_mutex);
09035 
09036 // This is used internally by all instances of linked_ptr<>.  It needs to be
09037 // a non-template class because different types of linked_ptr<> can refer to
09038 // the same object (linked_ptr<Superclass>(obj) vs linked_ptr<Subclass>(obj)).
09039 // So, it needs to be possible for different types of linked_ptr to participate
09040 // in the same circular linked list, so we need a single class type here.
09041 //
09042 // DO NOT USE THIS CLASS DIRECTLY YOURSELF.  Use linked_ptr<T>.
09043 class linked_ptr_internal {
09044  public:
09045   // Create a new circle that includes only this instance.
09046   void join_new() {
09047     next_ = this;
09048   }
09049 
09050   // Many linked_ptr operations may change p.link_ for some linked_ptr
09051   // variable p in the same circle as this object.  Therefore we need
09052   // to prevent two such operations from occurring concurrently.
09053   //
09054   // Note that different types of linked_ptr objects can coexist in a
09055   // circle (e.g. linked_ptr<Base>, linked_ptr<Derived1>, and
09056   // linked_ptr<Derived2>).  Therefore we must use a single mutex to
09057   // protect all linked_ptr objects.  This can create serious
09058   // contention in production code, but is acceptable in a testing
09059   // framework.
09060 
09061   // Join an existing circle.
09062   // L < g_linked_ptr_mutex
09063   void join(linked_ptr_internal const* ptr) {
09064     MutexLock lock(&g_linked_ptr_mutex);
09065 
09066     linked_ptr_internal const* p = ptr;
09067     while (p->next_ != ptr) p = p->next_;
09068     p->next_ = this;
09069     next_ = ptr;
09070   }
09071 
09072   // Leave whatever circle we're part of.  Returns true if we were the
09073   // last member of the circle.  Once this is done, you can join() another.
09074   // L < g_linked_ptr_mutex
09075   bool depart() {
09076     MutexLock lock(&g_linked_ptr_mutex);
09077 
09078     if (next_ == this) return true;
09079     linked_ptr_internal const* p = next_;
09080     while (p->next_ != this) p = p->next_;
09081     p->next_ = next_;
09082     return false;
09083   }
09084 
09085  private:
09086   mutable linked_ptr_internal const* next_;
09087 };
09088 
09089 template <typename T>
09090 class linked_ptr {
09091  public:
09092   typedef T element_type;
09093 
09094   // Take over ownership of a raw pointer.  This should happen as soon as
09095   // possible after the object is created.
09096   explicit linked_ptr(T* ptr = NULL) { capture(ptr); }
09097   ~linked_ptr() { depart(); }
09098 
09099   // Copy an existing linked_ptr<>, adding ourselves to the list of references.
09100   template <typename U> linked_ptr(linked_ptr<U> const& ptr) { copy(&ptr); }
09101   linked_ptr(linked_ptr const& ptr) {  // NOLINT
09102     assert(&ptr != this);
09103     copy(&ptr);
09104   }
09105 
09106   // Assignment releases the old value and acquires the new.
09107   template <typename U> linked_ptr& operator=(linked_ptr<U> const& ptr) {
09108     depart();
09109     copy(&ptr);
09110     return *this;
09111   }
09112 
09113   linked_ptr& operator=(linked_ptr const& ptr) {
09114     if (&ptr != this) {
09115       depart();
09116       copy(&ptr);
09117     }
09118     return *this;
09119   }
09120 
09121   // Smart pointer members.
09122   void reset(T* ptr = NULL) {
09123     depart();
09124     capture(ptr);
09125   }
09126   T* get() const { return value_; }
09127   T* operator->() const { return value_; }
09128   T& operator*() const { return *value_; }
09129 
09130   bool operator==(T* p) const { return value_ == p; }
09131   bool operator!=(T* p) const { return value_ != p; }
09132   template <typename U>
09133   bool operator==(linked_ptr<U> const& ptr) const {
09134     return value_ == ptr.get();
09135   }
09136   template <typename U>
09137   bool operator!=(linked_ptr<U> const& ptr) const {
09138     return value_ != ptr.get();
09139   }
09140 
09141  private:
09142   template <typename U>
09143   friend class linked_ptr;
09144 
09145   T* value_;
09146   linked_ptr_internal link_;
09147 
09148   void depart() {
09149     if (link_.depart()) delete value_;
09150   }
09151 
09152   void capture(T* ptr) {
09153     value_ = ptr;
09154     link_.join_new();
09155   }
09156 
09157   template <typename U> void copy(linked_ptr<U> const* ptr) {
09158     value_ = ptr->get();
09159     if (value_)
09160       link_.join(&ptr->link_);
09161     else
09162       link_.join_new();
09163   }
09164 };
09165 
09166 template<typename T> inline
09167 bool operator==(T* ptr, const linked_ptr<T>& x) {
09168   return ptr == x.get();
09169 }
09170 
09171 template<typename T> inline
09172 bool operator!=(T* ptr, const linked_ptr<T>& x) {
09173   return ptr != x.get();
09174 }
09175 
09176 // A function to convert T* into linked_ptr<T>
09177 // Doing e.g. make_linked_ptr(new FooBarBaz<type>(arg)) is a shorter notation
09178 // for linked_ptr<FooBarBaz<type> >(new FooBarBaz<type>(arg))
09179 template <typename T>
09180 linked_ptr<T> make_linked_ptr(T* ptr) {
09181   return linked_ptr<T>(ptr);
09182 }
09183 
09184 }  // namespace internal
09185 }  // namespace testing
09186 
09187 #endif  // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_LINKED_PTR_H_

09219 // Google Test - The Google C++ Testing Framework
09220 //
09221 // This file implements a universal value printer that can print a
09222 // value of any type T:
09223 //
09224 //   void ::testing::internal::UniversalPrinter<T>::Print(value, ostream_ptr);
09225 //
09226 // A user can teach this function how to print a class type T by
09227 // defining either operator<<() or PrintTo() in the namespace that
09228 // defines T.  More specifically, the FIRST defined function in the
09229 // following list will be used (assuming T is defined in namespace
09230 // foo):
09231 //
09232 //   1. foo::PrintTo(const T&, ostream*)
09233 //   2. operator<<(ostream&, const T&) defined in either foo or the
09234 //      global namespace.
09235 //
09236 // If none of the above is defined, it will print the debug string of
09237 // the value if it is a protocol buffer, or print the raw bytes in the
09238 // value otherwise.
09239 //
09240 // To aid debugging: when T is a reference type, the address of the
09241 // value is also printed; when T is a (const) char pointer, both the
09242 // pointer value and the NUL-terminated string it points to are
09243 // printed.
09244 //
09245 // We also provide some convenient wrappers:
09246 //
09247 //   // Prints a value to a string.  For a (const or not) char
09248 //   // pointer, the NUL-terminated string (but not the pointer) is
09249 //   // printed.
09250 //   std::string ::testing::PrintToString(const T& value);
09251 //
09252 //   // Prints a value tersely: for a reference type, the referenced
09253 //   // value (but not the address) is printed; for a (const or not) char
09254 //   // pointer, the NUL-terminated string (but not the pointer) is
09255 //   // printed.
09256 //   void ::testing::internal::UniversalTersePrint(const T& value, ostream*);
09257 //
09258 //   // Prints value using the type inferred by the compiler.  The difference
09259 //   // from UniversalTersePrint() is that this function prints both the
09260 //   // pointer and the NUL-terminated string for a (const or not) char pointer.
09261 //   void ::testing::internal::UniversalPrint(const T& value, ostream*);
09262 //
09263 //   // Prints the fields of a tuple tersely to a string vector, one
09264 //   // element for each field. Tuple support must be enabled in
09265 //   // gtest-port.h.
09266 //   std::vector<string> UniversalTersePrintTupleFieldsToStrings(
09267 //       const Tuple& value);
09268 //
09269 // Known limitation:
09270 //
09271 // The print primitives print the elements of an STL-style container
09272 // using the compiler-inferred type of *iter where iter is a
09273 // const_iterator of the container.  When const_iterator is an input
09274 // iterator but not a forward iterator, this inferred type may not
09275 // match value_type, and the print output may be incorrect.  In
09276 // practice, this is rarely a problem as for most containers
09277 // const_iterator is a forward iterator.  We'll fix this if there's an
09278 // actual need for it.  Note that this fix cannot rely on value_type
09279 // being defined as many user-defined container types don't have
09280 // value_type.
09281 
09282 #ifndef GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_PRINTERS_H_
09283 #define GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_PRINTERS_H_
09284 
09285 #include <ostream>  // NOLINT
09286 #include <sstream>
09287 #include <string>
09288 #include <utility>
09289 #include <vector>
09290 
09291 namespace testing {
09292 
09293 // Definitions in the 'internal' and 'internal2' name spaces are
09294 // subject to change without notice.  DO NOT USE THEM IN USER CODE!
09295 namespace internal2 {
09296 
09297 // Prints the given number of bytes in the given object to the given
09298 // ostream.
09299 GTEST_API_ void PrintBytesInObjectTo(const unsigned char* obj_bytes,
09300                                      size_t count,
09301                                      ::std::ostream* os);
09302 
09303 // For selecting which printer to use when a given type has neither <<
09304 // nor PrintTo().
09305 enum TypeKind {
09306   kProtobuf,              // a protobuf type
09307   kConvertibleToInteger,  // a type implicitly convertible to BiggestInt
09308                           // (e.g. a named or unnamed enum type)
09309   kOtherType              // anything else
09310 };
09311 
09312 // TypeWithoutFormatter<T, kTypeKind>::PrintValue(value, os) is called
09313 // by the universal printer to print a value of type T when neither
09314 // operator<< nor PrintTo() is defined for T, where kTypeKind is the
09315 // "kind" of T as defined by enum TypeKind.
09316 template <typename T, TypeKind kTypeKind>
09317 class TypeWithoutFormatter {
09318  public:
09319   // This default version is called when kTypeKind is kOtherType.
09320   static void PrintValue(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09321     PrintBytesInObjectTo(reinterpret_cast<const unsigned char*>(&value),
09322                          sizeof(value), os);
09323   }
09324 };
09325 
09326 // We print a protobuf using its ShortDebugString() when the string
09327 // doesn't exceed this many characters; otherwise we print it using
09328 // DebugString() for better readability.
09329 const size_t kProtobufOneLinerMaxLength = 50;
09330 
09331 template <typename T>
09332 class TypeWithoutFormatter<T, kProtobuf> {
09333  public:
09334   static void PrintValue(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09335     const ::testing::internal::string short_str = value.ShortDebugString();
09336     const ::testing::internal::string pretty_str =
09337         short_str.length() <= kProtobufOneLinerMaxLength ?
09338         short_str : ("\n" + value.DebugString());
09339     *os << ("<" + pretty_str + ">");
09340   }
09341 };
09342 
09343 template <typename T>
09344 class TypeWithoutFormatter<T, kConvertibleToInteger> {
09345  public:
09346   // Since T has no << operator or PrintTo() but can be implicitly
09347   // converted to BiggestInt, we print it as a BiggestInt.
09348   //
09349   // Most likely T is an enum type (either named or unnamed), in which
09350   // case printing it as an integer is the desired behavior.  In case
09351   // T is not an enum, printing it as an integer is the best we can do
09352   // given that it has no user-defined printer.
09353   static void PrintValue(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09354     const internal::BiggestInt kBigInt = value;
09355     *os << kBigInt;
09356   }
09357 };
09358 
09359 // Prints the given value to the given ostream.  If the value is a
09360 // protocol message, its debug string is printed; if it's an enum or
09361 // of a type implicitly convertible to BiggestInt, it's printed as an
09362 // integer; otherwise the bytes in the value are printed.  This is
09363 // what UniversalPrinter<T>::Print() does when it knows nothing about
09364 // type T and T has neither << operator nor PrintTo().
09365 //
09366 // A user can override this behavior for a class type Foo by defining
09367 // a << operator in the namespace where Foo is defined.
09368 //
09369 // We put this operator in namespace 'internal2' instead of 'internal'
09370 // to simplify the implementation, as much code in 'internal' needs to
09371 // use << in STL, which would conflict with our own << were it defined
09372 // in 'internal'.
09373 //
09374 // Note that this operator<< takes a generic std::basic_ostream<Char,
09375 // CharTraits> type instead of the more restricted std::ostream.  If
09376 // we define it to take an std::ostream instead, we'll get an
09377 // "ambiguous overloads" compiler error when trying to print a type
09378 // Foo that supports streaming to std::basic_ostream<Char,
09379 // CharTraits>, as the compiler cannot tell whether
09380 // operator<<(std::ostream&, const T&) or
09381 // operator<<(std::basic_stream<Char, CharTraits>, const Foo&) is more
09382 // specific.
09383 template <typename Char, typename CharTraits, typename T>
09384 ::std::basic_ostream<Char, CharTraits>& operator<<(
09385     ::std::basic_ostream<Char, CharTraits>& os, const T& x) {
09386   TypeWithoutFormatter<T,
09387       (internal::IsAProtocolMessage<T>::value ? kProtobuf :
09388        internal::ImplicitlyConvertible<const T&, internal::BiggestInt>::value ?
09389        kConvertibleToInteger : kOtherType)>::PrintValue(x, &os);
09390   return os;
09391 }
09392 
09393 }  // namespace internal2
09394 }  // namespace testing
09395 
09396 // This namespace MUST NOT BE NESTED IN ::testing, or the name look-up
09397 // magic needed for implementing UniversalPrinter won't work.
09398 namespace testing_internal {
09399 
09400 // Used to print a value that is not an STL-style container when the
09401 // user doesn't define PrintTo() for it.
09402 template <typename T>
09403 void DefaultPrintNonContainerTo(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09404   // With the following statement, during unqualified name lookup,
09405   // testing::internal2::operator<< appears as if it was declared in
09406   // the nearest enclosing namespace that contains both
09407   // ::testing_internal and ::testing::internal2, i.e. the global
09408   // namespace.  For more details, refer to the C++ Standard section
09409   // 7.3.4-1 [namespace.udir].  This allows us to fall back onto
09410   // testing::internal2::operator<< in case T doesn't come with a <<
09411   // operator.
09412   //
09413   // We cannot write 'using ::testing::internal2::operator<<;', which
09414   // gcc 3.3 fails to compile due to a compiler bug.
09415   using namespace ::testing::internal2;  // NOLINT
09416 
09417   // Assuming T is defined in namespace foo, in the next statement,
09418   // the compiler will consider all of:
09419   //
09420   //   1. foo::operator<< (thanks to Koenig look-up),
09421   //   2. ::operator<< (as the current namespace is enclosed in ::),
09422   //   3. testing::internal2::operator<< (thanks to the using statement above).
09423   //
09424   // The operator<< whose type matches T best will be picked.
09425   //
09426   // We deliberately allow #2 to be a candidate, as sometimes it's
09427   // impossible to define #1 (e.g. when foo is ::std, defining
09428   // anything in it is undefined behavior unless you are a compiler
09429   // vendor.).
09430   *os << value;
09431 }
09432 
09433 }  // namespace testing_internal
09434 
09435 namespace testing {
09436 namespace internal {
09437 
09438 // UniversalPrinter<T>::Print(value, ostream_ptr) prints the given
09439 // value to the given ostream.  The caller must ensure that
09440 // 'ostream_ptr' is not NULL, or the behavior is undefined.
09441 //
09442 // We define UniversalPrinter as a class template (as opposed to a
09443 // function template), as we need to partially specialize it for
09444 // reference types, which cannot be done with function templates.
09445 template <typename T>
09446 class UniversalPrinter;
09447 
09448 template <typename T>
09449 void UniversalPrint(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os);
09450 
09451 // Used to print an STL-style container when the user doesn't define
09452 // a PrintTo() for it.
09453 template <typename C>
09454 void DefaultPrintTo(IsContainer /* dummy */,
09455                     false_type /* is not a pointer */,
09456                     const C& container, ::std::ostream* os) {
09457   const size_t kMaxCount = 32;  // The maximum number of elements to print.
09458   *os << '{';
09459   size_t count = 0;
09460   for (typename C::const_iterator it = container.begin();
09461        it != container.end(); ++it, ++count) {
09462     if (count > 0) {
09463       *os << ',';
09464       if (count == kMaxCount) {  // Enough has been printed.
09465         *os << " ...";
09466         break;
09467       }
09468     }
09469     *os << ' ';
09470     // We cannot call PrintTo(*it, os) here as PrintTo() doesn't
09471     // handle *it being a native array.
09472     internal::UniversalPrint(*it, os);
09473   }
09474 
09475   if (count > 0) {
09476     *os << ' ';
09477   }
09478   *os << '}';
09479 }
09480 
09481 // Used to print a pointer that is neither a char pointer nor a member
09482 // pointer, when the user doesn't define PrintTo() for it.  (A member
09483 // variable pointer or member function pointer doesn't really point to
09484 // a location in the address space.  Their representation is
09485 // implementation-defined.  Therefore they will be printed as raw
09486 // bytes.)
09487 template <typename T>
09488 void DefaultPrintTo(IsNotContainer /* dummy */,
09489                     true_type /* is a pointer */,
09490                     T* p, ::std::ostream* os) {
09491   if (p == NULL) {
09492     *os << "NULL";
09493   } else {
09494     // C++ doesn't allow casting from a function pointer to any object
09495     // pointer.
09496     //
09497     // IsTrue() silences warnings: "Condition is always true",
09498     // "unreachable code".
09499     if (IsTrue(ImplicitlyConvertible<T*, const void*>::value)) {
09500       // T is not a function type.  We just call << to print p,
09501       // relying on ADL to pick up user-defined << for their pointer
09502       // types, if any.
09503       *os << p;
09504     } else {
09505       // T is a function type, so '*os << p' doesn't do what we want
09506       // (it just prints p as bool).  We want to print p as a const
09507       // void*.  However, we cannot cast it to const void* directly,
09508       // even using reinterpret_cast, as earlier versions of gcc
09509       // (e.g. 3.4.5) cannot compile the cast when p is a function
09510       // pointer.  Casting to UInt64 first solves the problem.
09511       *os << reinterpret_cast<const void*>(
09512           reinterpret_cast<internal::UInt64>(p));
09513     }
09514   }
09515 }
09516 
09517 // Used to print a non-container, non-pointer value when the user
09518 // doesn't define PrintTo() for it.
09519 template <typename T>
09520 void DefaultPrintTo(IsNotContainer /* dummy */,
09521                     false_type /* is not a pointer */,
09522                     const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09523   ::testing_internal::DefaultPrintNonContainerTo(value, os);
09524 }
09525 
09526 // Prints the given value using the << operator if it has one;
09527 // otherwise prints the bytes in it.  This is what
09528 // UniversalPrinter<T>::Print() does when PrintTo() is not specialized
09529 // or overloaded for type T.
09530 //
09531 // A user can override this behavior for a class type Foo by defining
09532 // an overload of PrintTo() in the namespace where Foo is defined.  We
09533 // give the user this option as sometimes defining a << operator for
09534 // Foo is not desirable (e.g. the coding style may prevent doing it,
09535 // or there is already a << operator but it doesn't do what the user
09536 // wants).
09537 template <typename T>
09538 void PrintTo(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09539   // DefaultPrintTo() is overloaded.  The type of its first two
09540   // arguments determine which version will be picked.  If T is an
09541   // STL-style container, the version for container will be called; if
09542   // T is a pointer, the pointer version will be called; otherwise the
09543   // generic version will be called.
09544   //
09545   // Note that we check for container types here, prior to we check
09546   // for protocol message types in our operator<<.  The rationale is:
09547   //
09548   // For protocol messages, we want to give people a chance to
09549   // override Google Mock's format by defining a PrintTo() or
09550   // operator<<.  For STL containers, other formats can be
09551   // incompatible with Google Mock's format for the container
09552   // elements; therefore we check for container types here to ensure
09553   // that our format is used.
09554   //
09555   // The second argument of DefaultPrintTo() is needed to bypass a bug
09556   // in Symbian's C++ compiler that prevents it from picking the right
09557   // overload between:
09558   //
09559   //   PrintTo(const T& x, ...);
09560   //   PrintTo(T* x, ...);
09561   DefaultPrintTo(IsContainerTest<T>(0), is_pointer<T>(), value, os);
09562 }
09563 
09564 // The following list of PrintTo() overloads tells
09565 // UniversalPrinter<T>::Print() how to print standard types (built-in
09566 // types, strings, plain arrays, and pointers).
09567 
09568 // Overloads for various char types.
09569 GTEST_API_ void PrintTo(unsigned char c, ::std::ostream* os);
09570 GTEST_API_ void PrintTo(signed char c, ::std::ostream* os);
09571 inline void PrintTo(char c, ::std::ostream* os) {
09572   // When printing a plain char, we always treat it as unsigned.  This
09573   // way, the output won't be affected by whether the compiler thinks
09574   // char is signed or not.
09575   PrintTo(static_cast<unsigned char>(c), os);
09576 }
09577 
09578 // Overloads for other simple built-in types.
09579 inline void PrintTo(bool x, ::std::ostream* os) {
09580   *os << (x ? "true" : "false");
09581 }
09582 
09583 // Overload for wchar_t type.
09584 // Prints a wchar_t as a symbol if it is printable or as its internal
09585 // code otherwise and also as its decimal code (except for L'\0').
09586 // The L'\0' char is printed as "L'\\0'". The decimal code is printed
09587 // as signed integer when wchar_t is implemented by the compiler
09588 // as a signed type and is printed as an unsigned integer when wchar_t
09589 // is implemented as an unsigned type.
09590 GTEST_API_ void PrintTo(wchar_t wc, ::std::ostream* os);

09598 // signed/unsigned char is often used for representing binary data, so
09599 // we print pointers to it as void* to be safe.
09600 inline void PrintTo(const signed char* s, ::std::ostream* os) {
09601   PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const void*>(s), os);
09602 }

09604   PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const void*>(s), os);

09607   PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const void*>(s), os);
09608 }

09610   PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const void*>(s), os);

09614 // short.  It defines _NATIVE_WCHAR_T_DEFINED when wchar_t is a native
09615 // type.  When wchar_t is a typedef, defining an overload for const
09616 // wchar_t* would cause unsigned short* be printed as a wide string,
09617 // possibly causing invalid memory accesses.
09618 #if !defined(_MSC_VER) || defined(_NATIVE_WCHAR_T_DEFINED)

09626 // Overload for C arrays.  Multi-dimensional arrays are printed
09627 // properly.

09629 // Prints the given number of elements in an array, without printing
09630 // the curly braces.
09631 template <typename T>
09632 void PrintRawArrayTo(const T a[], size_t count, ::std::ostream* os) {
09633   UniversalPrint(a[0], os);
09634   for (size_t i = 1; i != count; i++) {
09635     *os << ", ";
09636     UniversalPrint(a[i], os);
09637   }
09638 }

09749 // Overload for std::pair.
09750 template <typename T1, typename T2>
09751 void PrintTo(const ::std::pair<T1, T2>& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09752   *os << '(';
09753   // We cannot use UniversalPrint(value.first, os) here, as T1 may be
09754   // a reference type.  The same for printing value.second.
09755   UniversalPrinter<T1>::Print(value.first, os);
09756   *os << ", ";
09757   UniversalPrinter<T2>::Print(value.second, os);
09758   *os << ')';
09759 }
09760 
09761 // Implements printing a non-reference type T by letting the compiler
09762 // pick the right overload of PrintTo() for T.
09763 template <typename T>
09764 class UniversalPrinter {
09765  public:
09766   // MSVC warns about adding const to a function type, so we want to
09767   // disable the warning.
09768 #ifdef _MSC_VER
09769 # pragma warning(push)          // Saves the current warning state.
09770 # pragma warning(disable:4180)  // Temporarily disables warning 4180.
09771 #endif  // _MSC_VER
09772 
09773   // Note: we deliberately don't call this PrintTo(), as that name
09774   // conflicts with ::testing::internal::PrintTo in the body of the
09775   // function.
09776   static void Print(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09777     // By default, ::testing::internal::PrintTo() is used for printing
09778     // the value.
09779     //
09780     // Thanks to Koenig look-up, if T is a class and has its own
09781     // PrintTo() function defined in its namespace, that function will
09782     // be visible here.  Since it is more specific than the generic ones
09783     // in ::testing::internal, it will be picked by the compiler in the
09784     // following statement - exactly what we want.
09785     PrintTo(value, os);
09786   }
09787 
09788 #ifdef _MSC_VER
09789 # pragma warning(pop)           // Restores the warning state.
09790 #endif  // _MSC_VER
09791 };
09792 
09793 // UniversalPrintArray(begin, len, os) prints an array of 'len'
09794 // elements, starting at address 'begin'.
09795 template <typename T>
09796 void UniversalPrintArray(const T* begin, size_t len, ::std::ostream* os) {
09797   if (len == 0) {
09798     *os << "{}";
09799   } else {
09800     *os << "{ ";
09801     const size_t kThreshold = 18;
09802     const size_t kChunkSize = 8;
09803     // If the array has more than kThreshold elements, we'll have to
09804     // omit some details by printing only the first and the last
09805     // kChunkSize elements.
09806     // TODO(wan@google.com): let the user control the threshold using a flag.
09807     if (len <= kThreshold) {
09808       PrintRawArrayTo(begin, len, os);
09809     } else {
09810       PrintRawArrayTo(begin, kChunkSize, os);
09811       *os << ", ..., ";
09812       PrintRawArrayTo(begin + len - kChunkSize, kChunkSize, os);
09813     }
09814     *os << " }";
09815   }
09816 }
09817 // This overload prints a (const) char array compactly.
09818 GTEST_API_ void UniversalPrintArray(const char* begin,
09819                                     size_t len,
09820                                     ::std::ostream* os);
09821 
09822 // Implements printing an array type T[N].
09823 template <typename T, size_t N>
09824 class UniversalPrinter<T[N]> {
09825  public:
09826   // Prints the given array, omitting some elements when there are too
09827   // many.
09828   static void Print(const T (&a)[N], ::std::ostream* os) {
09829     UniversalPrintArray(a, N, os);
09830   }
09831 };
09832 
09833 // Implements printing a reference type T&.
09834 template <typename T>
09835 class UniversalPrinter<T&> {
09836  public:
09837   // MSVC warns about adding const to a function type, so we want to
09838   // disable the warning.
09839 #ifdef _MSC_VER
09840 # pragma warning(push)          // Saves the current warning state.
09841 # pragma warning(disable:4180)  // Temporarily disables warning 4180.
09842 #endif  // _MSC_VER
09843 
09844   static void Print(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09845     // Prints the address of the value.  We use reinterpret_cast here
09846     // as static_cast doesn't compile when T is a function type.
09847     *os << "@" << reinterpret_cast<const void*>(&value) << " ";
09848 
09849     // Then prints the value itself.
09850     UniversalPrint(value, os);
09851   }
09852 
09853 #ifdef _MSC_VER
09854 # pragma warning(pop)           // Restores the warning state.
09855 #endif  // _MSC_VER
09856 };
09857 
09858 // Prints a value tersely: for a reference type, the referenced value
09859 // (but not the address) is printed; for a (const) char pointer, the
09860 // NUL-terminated string (but not the pointer) is printed.
09861 template <typename T>
09862 void UniversalTersePrint(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09863   UniversalPrint(value, os);
09864 }
09865 inline void UniversalTersePrint(const char* str, ::std::ostream* os) {
09866   if (str == NULL) {
09867     *os << "NULL";
09868   } else {
09869     UniversalPrint(string(str), os);
09870   }
09871 }
09872 inline void UniversalTersePrint(char* str, ::std::ostream* os) {
09873   UniversalTersePrint(static_cast<const char*>(str), os);
09874 }
09875 
09876 // Prints a value using the type inferred by the compiler.  The
09877 // difference between this and UniversalTersePrint() is that for a
09878 // (const) char pointer, this prints both the pointer and the
09879 // NUL-terminated string.
09880 template <typename T>
09881 void UniversalPrint(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
09882   UniversalPrinter<T>::Print(value, os);
09883 }
09884 
09885 #if GTEST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE
09886 typedef ::std::vector<string> Strings;
09887 
09888 // This helper template allows PrintTo() for tuples and
09889 // UniversalTersePrintTupleFieldsToStrings() to be defined by
09890 // induction on the number of tuple fields.  The idea is that
09891 // TuplePrefixPrinter<N>::PrintPrefixTo(t, os) prints the first N
09892 // fields in tuple t, and can be defined in terms of
09893 // TuplePrefixPrinter<N - 1>.
09894 
09895 // The inductive case.
09896 template <size_t N>
09897 struct TuplePrefixPrinter {
09898   // Prints the first N fields of a tuple.
09899   template <typename Tuple>
09900   static void PrintPrefixTo(const Tuple& t, ::std::ostream* os) {
09901     TuplePrefixPrinter<N - 1>::PrintPrefixTo(t, os);
09902     *os << ", ";
09903     UniversalPrinter<typename ::std::tr1::tuple_element<N - 1, Tuple>::type>
09904         ::Print(::std::tr1::get<N - 1>(t), os);
09905   }
09906 
09907   // Tersely prints the first N fields of a tuple to a string vector,
09908   // one element for each field.
09909   template <typename Tuple>
09910   static void TersePrintPrefixToStrings(const Tuple& t, Strings* strings) {
09911     TuplePrefixPrinter<N - 1>::TersePrintPrefixToStrings(t, strings);
09912     ::std::stringstream ss;
09913     UniversalTersePrint(::std::tr1::get<N - 1>(t), &ss);
09914     strings->push_back(ss.str());
09915   }
09916 };
09917 
09918 // Base cases.
09919 template <>
09920 struct TuplePrefixPrinter<0> {
09921   template <typename Tuple>
09922   static void PrintPrefixTo(const Tuple&, ::std::ostream*) {}
09923 
09924   template <typename Tuple>
09925   static void TersePrintPrefixToStrings(const Tuple&, Strings*) {}
09926 };
09927 // We have to specialize the entire TuplePrefixPrinter<> class
09928 // template here, even though the definition of
09929 // TersePrintPrefixToStrings() is the same as the generic version, as
09930 // Embarcadero (formerly CodeGear, formerly Borland) C++ doesn't
09931 // support specializing a method template of a class template.
09932 template <>
09933 struct TuplePrefixPrinter<1> {
09934   template <typename Tuple>
09935   static void PrintPrefixTo(const Tuple& t, ::std::ostream* os) {
09936     UniversalPrinter<typename ::std::tr1::tuple_element<0, Tuple>::type>::
09937         Print(::std::tr1::get<0>(t), os);
09938   }
09939 
09940   template <typename Tuple>
09941   static void TersePrintPrefixToStrings(const Tuple& t, Strings* strings) {
09942     ::std::stringstream ss;
09943     UniversalTersePrint(::std::tr1::get<0>(t), &ss);
09944     strings->push_back(ss.str());
09945   }
09946 };
09947 
09948 // Helper function for printing a tuple.  T must be instantiated with
09949 // a tuple type.
09950 template <typename T>
09951 void PrintTupleTo(const T& t, ::std::ostream* os) {
09952   *os << "(";
09953   TuplePrefixPrinter< ::std::tr1::tuple_size<T>::value>::
09954       PrintPrefixTo(t, os);
09955   *os << ")";
09956 }
09957 
09958 // Prints the fields of a tuple tersely to a string vector, one
09959 // element for each field.  See the comment before
09960 // UniversalTersePrint() for how we define "tersely".
09961 template <typename Tuple>
09962 Strings UniversalTersePrintTupleFieldsToStrings(const Tuple& value) {
09963   Strings result;
09964   TuplePrefixPrinter< ::std::tr1::tuple_size<Tuple>::value>::
09965       TersePrintPrefixToStrings(value, &result);
09966   return result;
09967 }
09968 #endif  // GTEST_HAS_TR1_TUPLE
09969 
09970 }  // namespace internal
09971 
09972 template <typename T>
09973 ::std::string PrintToString(const T& value) {
09974   ::std::stringstream ss;
09975   internal::UniversalTersePrint(value, &ss);
09976   return ss.str();
09977 }

09988 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
09989 //
09990 // Outputs a message explaining invalid registration of different
09991 // fixture class for the same test case. This may happen when
09992 // TEST_P macro is used to define two tests with the same name
09993 // but in different namespaces.
09994 GTEST_API_ void ReportInvalidTestCaseType(const char* test_case_name,
09995                                           const char* file, int line);
09996 
09997 template <typename> class ParamGeneratorInterface;
09998 template <typename> class ParamGenerator;
09999 
10000 // Interface for iterating over elements provided by an implementation
10001 // of ParamGeneratorInterface<T>.
10002 template <typename T>
10003 class ParamIteratorInterface {
10004  public:
10005   virtual ~ParamIteratorInterface() {}
10006   // A pointer to the base generator instance.
10007   // Used only for the purposes of iterator comparison
10008   // to make sure that two iterators belong to the same generator.
10009   virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const = 0;
10010   // Advances iterator to point to the next element
10011   // provided by the generator. The caller is responsible
10012   // for not calling Advance() on an iterator equal to
10013   // BaseGenerator()->End().
10014   virtual void Advance() = 0;
10015   // Clones the iterator object. Used for implementing copy semantics
10016   // of ParamIterator<T>.
10017   virtual ParamIteratorInterface* Clone() const = 0;
10018   // Dereferences the current iterator and provides (read-only) access
10019   // to the pointed value. It is the caller's responsibility not to call
10020   // Current() on an iterator equal to BaseGenerator()->End().
10021   // Used for implementing ParamGenerator<T>::operator*().
10022   virtual const T* Current() const = 0;
10023   // Determines whether the given iterator and other point to the same
10024   // element in the sequence generated by the generator.
10025   // Used for implementing ParamGenerator<T>::operator==().
10026   virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface& other) const = 0;
10027 };
10028 
10029 // Class iterating over elements provided by an implementation of
10030 // ParamGeneratorInterface<T>. It wraps ParamIteratorInterface<T>
10031 // and implements the const forward iterator concept.
10032 template <typename T>
10033 class ParamIterator {
10034  public:
10035   typedef T value_type;
10036   typedef const T& reference;
10037   typedef ptrdiff_t difference_type;
10038 
10039   // ParamIterator assumes ownership of the impl_ pointer.
10040   ParamIterator(const ParamIterator& other) : impl_(other.impl_->Clone()) {}
10041   ParamIterator& operator=(const ParamIterator& other) {
10042     if (this != &other)
10043       impl_.reset(other.impl_->Clone());
10044     return *this;
10045   }
10046 
10047   const T& operator*() const { return *impl_->Current(); }
10048   const T* operator->() const { return impl_->Current(); }
10049   // Prefix version of operator++.
10050   ParamIterator& operator++() {
10051     impl_->Advance();
10052     return *this;
10053   }
10054   // Postfix version of operator++.
10055   ParamIterator operator++(int /*unused*/) {
10056     ParamIteratorInterface<T>* clone = impl_->Clone();
10057     impl_->Advance();
10058     return ParamIterator(clone);
10059   }
10060   bool operator==(const ParamIterator& other) const {
10061     return impl_.get() == other.impl_.get() || impl_->Equals(*other.impl_);
10062   }
10063   bool operator!=(const ParamIterator& other) const {
10064     return !(*this == other);
10065   }
10066 
10067  private:
10068   friend class ParamGenerator<T>;
10069   explicit ParamIterator(ParamIteratorInterface<T>* impl) : impl_(impl) {}
10070   scoped_ptr<ParamIteratorInterface<T> > impl_;
10071 };
10072 
10073 // ParamGeneratorInterface<T> is the binary interface to access generators
10074 // defined in other translation units.
10075 template <typename T>
10076 class ParamGeneratorInterface {
10077  public:
10078   typedef T ParamType;
10079 
10080   virtual ~ParamGeneratorInterface() {}
10081 
10082   // Generator interface definition
10083   virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const = 0;
10084   virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const = 0;
10085 };
10086 
10087 // Wraps ParamGeneratorInterface<T> and provides general generator syntax
10088 // compatible with the STL Container concept.
10089 // This class implements copy initialization semantics and the contained
10090 // ParamGeneratorInterface<T> instance is shared among all copies
10091 // of the original object. This is possible because that instance is immutable.
10092 template<typename T>
10093 class ParamGenerator {
10094  public:
10095   typedef ParamIterator<T> iterator;
10096 
10097   explicit ParamGenerator(ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* impl) : impl_(impl) {}
10098   ParamGenerator(const ParamGenerator& other) : impl_(other.impl_) {}
10099 
10100   ParamGenerator& operator=(const ParamGenerator& other) {
10101     impl_ = other.impl_;
10102     return *this;
10103   }
10104 
10105   iterator begin() const { return iterator(impl_->Begin()); }
10106   iterator end() const { return iterator(impl_->End()); }
10107 
10108  private:
10109   linked_ptr<const ParamGeneratorInterface<T> > impl_;
10110 };
10111 
10112 // Generates values from a range of two comparable values. Can be used to
10113 // generate sequences of user-defined types that implement operator+() and
10114 // operator<().
10115 // This class is used in the Range() function.
10116 template <typename T, typename IncrementT>
10117 class RangeGenerator : public ParamGeneratorInterface<T> {
10118  public:
10119   RangeGenerator(T begin, T end, IncrementT step)
10120       : begin_(begin), end_(end),
10121         step_(step), end_index_(CalculateEndIndex(begin, end, step)) {}
10122   virtual ~RangeGenerator() {}
10123 
10124   virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const {
10125     return new Iterator(this, begin_, 0, step_);
10126   }
10127   virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const {
10128     return new Iterator(this, end_, end_index_, step_);
10129   }
10130 
10131  private:
10132   class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<T> {
10133    public:
10134     Iterator(const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* base, T value, int index,
10135              IncrementT step)
10136         : base_(base), value_(value), index_(index), step_(step) {}
10137     virtual ~Iterator() {}
10138 
10139     virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const {
10140       return base_;
10141     }
10142     virtual void Advance() {
10143       value_ = value_ + step_;
10144       index_++;
10145     }
10146     virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Clone() const {
10147       return new Iterator(*this);
10148     }
10149     virtual const T* Current() const { return &value_; }
10150     virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<T>& other) const {
10151       // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
10152       // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
10153       GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
10154           << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
10155           << "from different generators." << std::endl;
10156       const int other_index =
10157           CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other)->index_;
10158       return index_ == other_index;
10159     }
10160 
10161    private:
10162     Iterator(const Iterator& other)
10163         : ParamIteratorInterface<T>(),
10164           base_(other.base_), value_(other.value_), index_(other.index_),
10165           step_(other.step_) {}
10166 
10167     // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
10168     void operator=(const Iterator& other);
10169 
10170     const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* const base_;
10171     T value_;
10172     int index_;
10173     const IncrementT step_;
10174   };  // class RangeGenerator::Iterator
10175 
10176   static int CalculateEndIndex(const T& begin,
10177                                const T& end,
10178                                const IncrementT& step) {
10179     int end_index = 0;
10180     for (T i = begin; i < end; i = i + step)
10181       end_index++;
10182     return end_index;
10183   }
10184 
10185   // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
10186   void operator=(const RangeGenerator& other);
10187 
10188   const T begin_;
10189   const T end_;
10190   const IncrementT step_;
10191   // The index for the end() iterator. All the elements in the generated
10192   // sequence are indexed (0-based) to aid iterator comparison.
10193   const int end_index_;
10194 };  // class RangeGenerator

10197 // Generates values from a pair of STL-style iterators. Used in the
10198 // ValuesIn() function. The elements are copied from the source range
10199 // since the source can be located on the stack, and the generator
10200 // is likely to persist beyond that stack frame.
10201 template <typename T>
10202 class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator : public ParamGeneratorInterface<T> {
10203  public:
10204   template <typename ForwardIterator>
10205   ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator(ForwardIterator begin, ForwardIterator end)
10206       : container_(begin, end) {}
10207   virtual ~ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator() {}
10208 
10209   virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const {
10210     return new Iterator(this, container_.begin());
10211   }
10212   virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const {
10213     return new Iterator(this, container_.end());
10214   }
10215 
10216  private:
10217   typedef typename ::std::vector<T> ContainerType;
10218 
10219   class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<T> {
10220    public:
10221     Iterator(const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* base,
10222              typename ContainerType::const_iterator iterator)
10223         : base_(base), iterator_(iterator) {}
10224     virtual ~Iterator() {}
10225 
10226     virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const {
10227       return base_;
10228     }
10229     virtual void Advance() {
10230       ++iterator_;
10231       value_.reset();
10232     }
10233     virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Clone() const {
10234       return new Iterator(*this);
10235     }
10236     // We need to use cached value referenced by iterator_ because *iterator_
10237     // can return a temporary object (and of type other then T), so just
10238     // having "return &*iterator_;" doesn't work.
10239     // value_ is updated here and not in Advance() because Advance()
10240     // can advance iterator_ beyond the end of the range, and we cannot
10241     // detect that fact. The client code, on the other hand, is
10242     // responsible for not calling Current() on an out-of-range iterator.
10243     virtual const T* Current() const {
10244       if (value_.get() == NULL)
10245         value_.reset(new T(*iterator_));
10246       return value_.get();
10247     }
10248     virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<T>& other) const {
10249       // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
10250       // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
10251       GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
10252           << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
10253           << "from different generators." << std::endl;
10254       return iterator_ ==
10255           CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other)->iterator_;
10256     }
10257 
10258    private:
10259     Iterator(const Iterator& other)
10260           // The explicit constructor call suppresses a false warning
10261           // emitted by gcc when supplied with the -Wextra option.
10262         : ParamIteratorInterface<T>(),
10263           base_(other.base_),
10264           iterator_(other.iterator_) {}
10265 
10266     const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* const base_;
10267     typename ContainerType::const_iterator iterator_;
10268     // A cached value of *iterator_. We keep it here to allow access by
10269     // pointer in the wrapping iterator's operator->().
10270     // value_ needs to be mutable to be accessed in Current().
10271     // Use of scoped_ptr helps manage cached value's lifetime,
10272     // which is bound by the lifespan of the iterator itself.
10273     mutable scoped_ptr<const T> value_;
10274   };  // class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator::Iterator
10275 
10276   // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
10277   void operator=(const ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator& other);
10278 
10279   const ContainerType container_;
10280 };  // class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator
